1157// Flags for ImGui::BeginTable()
1158// - Important! Sizing policies have complex and subtle side effects, much more so than you would expect.
1159// Read comments/demos carefully + experiment with live demos to get acquainted with them.
1160// - The DEFAULT sizing policies are:
1161// - Default to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit if ScrollX is on, or if host window has ImGuiWindowFlags_AlwaysAutoResize.
1162// - Default to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame if ScrollX is off.
1163// - When ScrollX is off:
1164// - Table defaults to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame -> all Columns defaults to ImGuiTableColumnFlags_WidthStretch with same weight.
1165// - Columns sizing policy allowed: Stretch (default), Fixed/Auto.
1166// - Fixed Columns (if any) will generally obtain their requested width (unless the table cannot fit them all).
1167// - Stretch Columns will share the remaining width according to their respective weight.
1168// - Mixed Fixed/Stretch columns is possible but has various side-effects on resizing behaviors.
1169// The typical use of mixing sizing policies is: any number of LEADING Fixed columns, followed by one or two TRAILING Stretch columns.
1170// (this is because the visible order of columns have subtle but necessary effects on how they react to manual resizing).
1171// - When ScrollX is on:
1172// - Table defaults to ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit -> all Columns defaults to ImGuiTableColumnFlags_WidthFixed
1173// - Columns sizing policy allowed: Fixed/Auto mostly.
1174// - Fixed Columns can be enlarged as needed. Table will show an horizontal scrollbar if needed.
1175// - When using auto-resizing (non-resizable) fixed columns, querying the content width to use item right-alignment e.g. SetNextItemWidth(-FLT_MIN) doesn't make sense, would create a feedback loop.
1176// - Using Stretch columns OFTEN DOES NOT MAKE SENSE if ScrollX is on, UNLESS you have specified a value for 'inner_width' in BeginTable().
1177// If you specify a value for 'inner_width' then effectively the scrolling space is known and Stretch or mixed Fixed/Stretch columns become meaningful again.
1178// - Read on documentation at the top of imgui_tables.cpp for details.
1179enum ImGuiTableFlags_
1180{
1181 // Features
1182 ImGuiTableFlags_None = 0,
1183 ImGuiTableFlags_Resizable = 1 << 0, // Enable resizing columns.
1184 ImGuiTableFlags_Reorderable = 1 << 1, // Enable reordering columns in header row (need calling TableSetupColumn() + TableHeadersRow() to display headers)
1185 ImGuiTableFlags_Hideable = 1 << 2, // Enable hiding/disabling columns in context menu.
1186 ImGuiTableFlags_Sortable = 1 << 3, // Enable sorting. Call TableGetSortSpecs() to obtain sort specs. Also see ImGuiTableFlags_SortMulti and ImGuiTableFlags_SortTristate.
1187 ImGuiTableFlags_NoSavedSettings = 1 << 4, // Disable persisting columns order, width and sort settings in the .ini file.
1188 ImGuiTableFlags_ContextMenuInBody = 1 << 5, // Right-click on columns body/contents will display table context menu. By default it is available in TableHeadersRow().
1189 // Decorations
1190 ImGuiTableFlags_RowBg = 1 << 6, // Set each RowBg color with ImGuiCol_TableRowBg or ImGuiCol_TableRowBgAlt (equivalent of calling TableSetBgColor with ImGuiTableBgFlags_RowBg0 on each row manually)
1191 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerH = 1 << 7, // Draw horizontal borders between rows.
1192 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterH = 1 << 8, // Draw horizontal borders at the top and bottom.
1193 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerV = 1 << 9, // Draw vertical borders between columns.
1194 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterV = 1 << 10, // Draw vertical borders on the left and right sides.
1195 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersH = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerH | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterH, // Draw horizontal borders.
1196 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersV = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerV | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterV, // Draw vertical borders.
1197 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInner = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerV | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInnerH, // Draw inner borders.
1198 ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuter = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterV | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuterH, // Draw outer borders.
1199 ImGuiTableFlags_Borders = ImGuiTableFlags_BordersInner | ImGuiTableFlags_BordersOuter, // Draw all borders.
1200 ImGuiTableFlags_NoBordersInBody = 1 << 11, // [ALPHA] Disable vertical borders in columns Body (borders will always appears in Headers). -> May move to style
1201 ImGuiTableFlags_NoBordersInBodyUntilResize = 1 << 12, // [ALPHA] Disable vertical borders in columns Body until hovered for resize (borders will always appears in Headers). -> May move to style
1202 // Sizing Policy (read above for defaults)
1203 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit = 1 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthFixed or _WidthAuto (if resizable or not resizable), matching contents width.
1204 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedSame = 2 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthFixed or _WidthAuto (if resizable or not resizable), matching the maximum contents width of all columns. Implicitly enable ImGuiTableFlags_NoKeepColumnsVisible.
1205 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchProp = 3 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthStretch with default weights proportional to each columns contents widths.
1206 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame = 4 << 13, // Columns default to _WidthStretch with default weights all equal, unless overridden by TableSetupColumn().
1207 // Sizing Extra Options
1208 ImGuiTableFlags_NoHostExtendX = 1 << 16, // Make outer width auto-fit to columns, overriding outer_size.x value. Only available when ScrollX/ScrollY are disabled and Stretch columns are not used.
1209 ImGuiTableFlags_NoHostExtendY = 1 << 17, // Make outer height stop exactly at outer_size.y (prevent auto-extending table past the limit). Only available when ScrollX/ScrollY are disabled. Data below the limit will be clipped and not visible.
1210 ImGuiTableFlags_NoKeepColumnsVisible = 1 << 18, // Disable keeping column always minimally visible when ScrollX is off and table gets too small. Not recommended if columns are resizable.
1211 ImGuiTableFlags_PreciseWidths = 1 << 19, // Disable distributing remainder width to stretched columns (width allocation on a 100-wide table with 3 columns: Without this flag: 33,33,34. With this flag: 33,33,33). With larger number of columns, resizing will appear to be less smooth.
1212 // Clipping
1213 ImGuiTableFlags_NoClip = 1 << 20, // Disable clipping rectangle for every individual columns (reduce draw command count, items will be able to overflow into other columns). Generally incompatible with TableSetupScrollFreeze().
1214 // Padding
1215 ImGuiTableFlags_PadOuterX = 1 << 21, // Default if BordersOuterV is on. Enable outer-most padding. Generally desirable if you have headers.
1216 ImGuiTableFlags_NoPadOuterX = 1 << 22, // Default if BordersOuterV is off. Disable outer-most padding.
1217 ImGuiTableFlags_NoPadInnerX = 1 << 23, // Disable inner padding between columns (double inner padding if BordersOuterV is on, single inner padding if BordersOuterV is off).
1218 // Scrolling
1219 ImGuiTableFlags_ScrollX = 1 << 24, // Enable horizontal scrolling. Require 'outer_size' parameter of BeginTable() to specify the container size. Changes default sizing policy. Because this create a child window, ScrollY is currently generally recommended when using ScrollX.
1220 ImGuiTableFlags_ScrollY = 1 << 25, // Enable vertical scrolling. Require 'outer_size' parameter of BeginTable() to specify the container size.
1221 // Sorting
1222 ImGuiTableFlags_SortMulti = 1 << 26, // Hold shift when clicking headers to sort on multiple column. TableGetSortSpecs() may return specs where (SpecsCount > 1).
1223 ImGuiTableFlags_SortTristate = 1 << 27, // Allow no sorting, disable default sorting. TableGetSortSpecs() may return specs where (SpecsCount == 0).
1224
1225 // [Internal] Combinations and masks
1226 ImGuiTableFlags_SizingMask_ = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit | ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedSame | ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchProp | ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame
1227
1228 // Obsolete names (will be removed soon)
1229#ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
1230 //, ImGuiTableFlags_ColumnsWidthFixed = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit, ImGuiTableFlags_ColumnsWidthStretch = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame // WIP Tables 2020/12
1231 //, ImGuiTableFlags_SizingPolicyFixed = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingFixedFit, ImGuiTableFlags_SizingPolicyStretch = ImGuiTableFlags_SizingStretchSame // WIP Tables 2021/01
1232#endif
1233};

1284// Enum for ImGui::TableSetBgColor()
1285// Background colors are rendering in 3 layers:
1286// - Layer 0: draw with RowBg0 color if set, otherwise draw with ColumnBg0 if set.
1287// - Layer 1: draw with RowBg1 color if set, otherwise draw with ColumnBg1 if set.
1288// - Layer 2: draw with CellBg color if set.
1289// The purpose of the two row/columns layers is to let you decide if a background color changes should override or blend with the existing color.
1290// When using ImGuiTableFlags_RowBg on the table, each row has the RowBg0 color automatically set for odd/even rows.
1291// If you set the color of RowBg0 target, your color will override the existing RowBg0 color.
1292// If you set the color of RowBg1 or ColumnBg1 target, your color will blend over the RowBg0 color.
1293enum ImGuiTableBgTarget_
1294{
1295 ImGuiTableBgTarget_None = 0,
1296 ImGuiTableBgTarget_RowBg0 = 1, // Set row background color 0 (generally used for background, automatically set when ImGuiTableFlags_RowBg is used)
1297 ImGuiTableBgTarget_RowBg1 = 2, // Set row background color 1 (generally used for selection marking)
1298 ImGuiTableBgTarget_CellBg = 3 // Set cell background color (top-most color)
1299};

1308 ImGuiFocusedFlags_NoPopupHierarchy = 1 << 3, // Do not consider popup hierarchy (do not treat popup emitter as parent of popup) (when used with _ChildWindows or _RootWindow)

1349// Flags for ImGui::BeginDragDropSource(), ImGui::AcceptDragDropPayload()
1350enum ImGuiDragDropFlags_
1351{
1352 ImGuiDragDropFlags_None = 0,
1353 // BeginDragDropSource() flags
1354 ImGuiDragDropFlags_SourceNoPreviewTooltip = 1 << 0, // By default, a successful call to BeginDragDropSource opens a tooltip so you can display a preview or description of the source contents. This flag disable this behavior.
1355 ImGuiDragDropFlags_SourceNoDisableHover = 1 << 1, // By default, when dragging we clear data so that IsItemHovered() will return false, to avoid subsequent user code submitting tooltips. This flag disable this behavior so you can still call IsItemHovered() on the source item.
1356 ImGuiDragDropFlags_SourceNoHoldToOpenOthers = 1 << 2, // Disable the behavior that allows to open tree nodes and collapsing header by holding over them while dragging a source item.
1357 ImGuiDragDropFlags_SourceAllowNullID = 1 << 3, // Allow items such as Text(), Image() that have no unique identifier to be used as drag source, by manufacturing a temporary identifier based on their window-relative position. This is extremely unusual within the dear imgui ecosystem and so we made it explicit.
1358 ImGuiDragDropFlags_SourceExtern = 1 << 4, // External source (from outside of dear imgui), won't attempt to read current item/window info. Will always return true. Only one Extern source can be active simultaneously.
1359 ImGuiDragDropFlags_SourceAutoExpirePayload = 1 << 5, // Automatically expire the payload if the source cease to be submitted (otherwise payloads are persisting while being dragged)
1360 // AcceptDragDropPayload() flags
1361 ImGuiDragDropFlags_AcceptBeforeDelivery = 1 << 10, // AcceptDragDropPayload() will returns true even before the mouse button is released. You can then call IsDelivery() to test if the payload needs to be delivered.
1362 ImGuiDragDropFlags_AcceptNoDrawDefaultRect = 1 << 11, // Do not draw the default highlight rectangle when hovering over target.
1363 ImGuiDragDropFlags_AcceptNoPreviewTooltip = 1 << 12, // Request hiding the BeginDragDropSource tooltip from the BeginDragDropTarget site.
1364 ImGuiDragDropFlags_AcceptPeekOnly = ImGuiDragDropFlags_AcceptBeforeDelivery | ImGuiDragDropFlags_AcceptNoDrawDefaultRect // For peeking ahead and inspecting the payload before delivery.
1365};

1488 // Keyboard Modifiers (explicitly submitted by backend via AddKeyEvent() calls)
1489 // - This is mirroring the data also written to io.KeyCtrl, io.KeyShift, io.KeyAlt, io.KeySuper, in a format allowing
1490 // them to be accessed via standard key API, allowing calls such as IsKeyPressed(), IsKeyReleased(), querying duration etc.
1491 // - Code polling every keys (e.g. an interface to detect a key press for input mapping) might want to ignore those
1492 // and prefer using the real keys (e.g. ImGuiKey_LeftCtrl, ImGuiKey_RightCtrl instead of ImGuiKey_ModCtrl).
1493 // - In theory the value of keyboard modifiers should be roughly equivalent to a logical or of the equivalent left/right keys.
1494 // In practice: it's complicated; mods are often provided from different sources. Keyboard layout, IME, sticky keys and
1495 // backends tend to interfere and break that equivalence. The safer decision is to relay that ambiguity down to the end-user...
1496 ImGuiKey_ModCtrl, ImGuiKey_ModShift, ImGuiKey_ModAlt, ImGuiKey_ModSuper,
1497
1498 // End of list
1499 ImGuiKey_COUNT, // No valid ImGuiKey is ever greater than this value

1509#else

1529// Gamepad/Keyboard navigation
1530// Since >= 1.87 backends you generally don't need to care about this enum since io.NavInputs[] is setup automatically. This might become private/internal some day.
1531// Keyboard: Set io.ConfigFlags |= ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableKeyboard to enable. NewFrame() will automatically fill io.NavInputs[] based on your io.AddKeyEvent() calls.
1532// Gamepad: Set io.ConfigFlags |= ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableGamepad to enable. Backend: set ImGuiBackendFlags_HasGamepad and fill the io.NavInputs[] fields before calling NewFrame(). Note that io.NavInputs[] is cleared by EndFrame().
1533// Read instructions in imgui.cpp for more details. Download PNG/PSD at http://dearimgui.org/controls_sheets.
1534enum ImGuiNavInput_
1535{
1536 // Gamepad Mapping
1537 ImGuiNavInput_Activate, // Activate / Open / Toggle / Tweak value // e.g. Cross (PS4), A (Xbox), A (Switch), Space (Keyboard)
1538 ImGuiNavInput_Cancel, // Cancel / Close / Exit // e.g. Circle (PS4), B (Xbox), B (Switch), Escape (Keyboard)
1539 ImGuiNavInput_Input, // Text input / On-Screen keyboard // e.g. Triang.(PS4), Y (Xbox), X (Switch), Return (Keyboard)
1540 ImGuiNavInput_Menu, // Tap: Toggle menu / Hold: Focus, Move, Resize // e.g. Square (PS4), X (Xbox), Y (Switch), Alt (Keyboard)
1541 ImGuiNavInput_DpadLeft, // Move / Tweak / Resize window (w/ PadMenu) // e.g. D-pad Left/Right/Up/Down (Gamepads), Arrow keys (Keyboard)
1542 ImGuiNavInput_DpadRight, //
1543 ImGuiNavInput_DpadUp, //
1544 ImGuiNavInput_DpadDown, //
1545 ImGuiNavInput_LStickLeft, // Scroll / Move window (w/ PadMenu) // e.g. Left Analog Stick Left/Right/Up/Down
1546 ImGuiNavInput_LStickRight, //
1547 ImGuiNavInput_LStickUp, //
1548 ImGuiNavInput_LStickDown, //
1549 ImGuiNavInput_FocusPrev, // Focus Next window (w/ PadMenu) // e.g. L1 or L2 (PS4), LB or LT (Xbox), L or ZL (Switch)
1550 ImGuiNavInput_FocusNext, // Focus Prev window (w/ PadMenu) // e.g. R1 or R2 (PS4), RB or RT (Xbox), R or ZL (Switch)
1551 ImGuiNavInput_TweakSlow, // Slower tweaks // e.g. L1 or L2 (PS4), LB or LT (Xbox), L or ZL (Switch)
1552 ImGuiNavInput_TweakFast, // Faster tweaks // e.g. R1 or R2 (PS4), RB or RT (Xbox), R or ZL (Switch)
1553
1554 // [Internal] Don't use directly! This is used internally to differentiate keyboard from gamepad inputs for behaviors that require to differentiate them.
1555 // Keyboard behavior that have no corresponding gamepad mapping (e.g. CTRL+TAB) will be directly reading from keyboard keys instead of io.NavInputs[].
1556 ImGuiNavInput_KeyLeft_, // Move left // = Arrow keys
1557 ImGuiNavInput_KeyRight_, // Move right
1558 ImGuiNavInput_KeyUp_, // Move up
1559 ImGuiNavInput_KeyDown_, // Move down
1560 ImGuiNavInput_COUNT
1561};

1563// Configuration flags stored in io.ConfigFlags. Set by user/application.
1564enum ImGuiConfigFlags_
1565{
1566 ImGuiConfigFlags_None = 0,
1567 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableKeyboard = 1 << 0, // Master keyboard navigation enable flag. NewFrame() will automatically fill io.NavInputs[] based on io.AddKeyEvent() calls
1568 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableGamepad = 1 << 1, // Master gamepad navigation enable flag. This is mostly to instruct your imgui backend to fill io.NavInputs[]. Backend also needs to set ImGuiBackendFlags_HasGamepad.
1569 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableSetMousePos = 1 << 2, // Instruct navigation to move the mouse cursor. May be useful on TV/console systems where moving a virtual mouse is awkward. Will update io.MousePos and set io.WantSetMousePos=true. If enabled you MUST honor io.WantSetMousePos requests in your backend, otherwise ImGui will react as if the mouse is jumping around back and forth.
1570 ImGuiConfigFlags_NavNoCaptureKeyboard = 1 << 3, // Instruct navigation to not set the io.WantCaptureKeyboard flag when io.NavActive is set.
1571 ImGuiConfigFlags_NoMouse = 1 << 4, // Instruct imgui to clear mouse position/buttons in NewFrame(). This allows ignoring the mouse information set by the backend.
1572 ImGuiConfigFlags_NoMouseCursorChange = 1 << 5, // Instruct backend to not alter mouse cursor shape and visibility. Use if the backend cursor changes are interfering with yours and you don't want to use SetMouseCursor() to change mouse cursor. You may want to honor requests from imgui by reading GetMouseCursor() yourself instead.
1573
1574 // [BETA] Docking
1575 ImGuiConfigFlags_DockingEnable = 1 << 6, // Docking enable flags.
1576
1577 // [BETA] Viewports
1578 // When using viewports it is recommended that your default value for ImGuiCol_WindowBg is opaque (Alpha=1.0) so transition to a viewport won't be noticeable.
1579 ImGuiConfigFlags_ViewportsEnable = 1 << 10, // Viewport enable flags (require both ImGuiBackendFlags_PlatformHasViewports + ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasViewports set by the respective backends)
1580 ImGuiConfigFlags_DpiEnableScaleViewports= 1 << 14, // [BETA: Don't use] FIXME-DPI: Reposition and resize imgui windows when the DpiScale of a viewport changed (mostly useful for the main viewport hosting other window). Note that resizing the main window itself is up to your application.
1581 ImGuiConfigFlags_DpiEnableScaleFonts = 1 << 15, // [BETA: Don't use] FIXME-DPI: Request bitmap-scaled fonts to match DpiScale. This is a very low-quality workaround. The correct way to handle DPI is _currently_ to replace the atlas and/or fonts in the Platform_OnChangedViewport callback, but this is all early work in progress.
1582
1583 // User storage (to allow your backend/engine to communicate to code that may be shared between multiple projects. Those flags are NOT used by core Dear ImGui)
1584 ImGuiConfigFlags_IsSRGB = 1 << 20, // Application is SRGB-aware.
1585 ImGuiConfigFlags_IsTouchScreen = 1 << 21 // Application is using a touch screen instead of a mouse.
1586};

1588// Backend capabilities flags stored in io.BackendFlags. Set by imgui_impl_xxx or custom backend.
1589enum ImGuiBackendFlags_
1590{
1591 ImGuiBackendFlags_None = 0,
1592 ImGuiBackendFlags_HasGamepad = 1 << 0, // Backend Platform supports gamepad and currently has one connected.
1593 ImGuiBackendFlags_HasMouseCursors = 1 << 1, // Backend Platform supports honoring GetMouseCursor() value to change the OS cursor shape.
1594 ImGuiBackendFlags_HasSetMousePos = 1 << 2, // Backend Platform supports io.WantSetMousePos requests to reposition the OS mouse position (only used if ImGuiConfigFlags_NavEnableSetMousePos is set).
1595 ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset = 1 << 3, // Backend Renderer supports ImDrawCmd::VtxOffset. This enables output of large meshes (64K+ vertices) while still using 16-bit indices.
1596
1597 // [BETA] Viewports
1598 ImGuiBackendFlags_PlatformHasViewports = 1 << 10, // Backend Platform supports multiple viewports.
1599 ImGuiBackendFlags_HasMouseHoveredViewport=1 << 11, // Backend Platform supports calling io.AddMouseViewportEvent() with the viewport under the mouse. IF POSSIBLE, ignore viewports with the ImGuiViewportFlags_NoInputs flag (Win32 backend, GLFW 3.30+ backend can do this, SDL backend cannot). If this cannot be done, Dear ImGui needs to use a flawed heuristic to find the viewport under.
1600 ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasViewports = 1 << 12 // Backend Renderer supports multiple viewports.
1601};

1727 ImGuiColorEditFlags_NoDragDrop = 1 << 9, // // ColorEdit: disable drag and drop target. ColorButton: disable drag and drop source.
1728 ImGuiColorEditFlags_NoBorder = 1 << 10, // // ColorButton: disable border (which is enforced by default)
1729
1730 // User Options (right-click on widget to change some of them).
1731 ImGuiColorEditFlags_AlphaBar = 1 << 16, // // ColorEdit, ColorPicker: show vertical alpha bar/gradient in picker.
1732 ImGuiColorEditFlags_AlphaPreview = 1 << 17, // // ColorEdit, ColorPicker, ColorButton: display preview as a transparent color over a checkerboard, instead of opaque.
1733 ImGuiColorEditFlags_AlphaPreviewHalf= 1 << 18, // // ColorEdit, ColorPicker, ColorButton: display half opaque / half checkerboard, instead of opaque.
1734 ImGuiColorEditFlags_HDR = 1 << 19, // // (WIP) ColorEdit: Currently only disable 0.0f..1.0f limits in RGBA edition (note: you probably want to use ImGuiColorEditFlags_Float flag as well).
1735 ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayRGB = 1 << 20, // [Display] // ColorEdit: override _display_ type among RGB/HSV/Hex. ColorPicker: select any combination using one or more of RGB/HSV/Hex.
1736 ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHSV = 1 << 21, // [Display] // "
1737 ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHex = 1 << 22, // [Display] // "
1738 ImGuiColorEditFlags_Uint8 = 1 << 23, // [DataType] // ColorEdit, ColorPicker, ColorButton: _display_ values formatted as 0..255.
1739 ImGuiColorEditFlags_Float = 1 << 24, // [DataType] // ColorEdit, ColorPicker, ColorButton: _display_ values formatted as 0.0f..1.0f floats instead of 0..255 integers. No round-trip of value via integers.
1740 ImGuiColorEditFlags_PickerHueBar = 1 << 25, // [Picker] // ColorPicker: bar for Hue, rectangle for Sat/Value.
1741 ImGuiColorEditFlags_PickerHueWheel = 1 << 26, // [Picker] // ColorPicker: wheel for Hue, triangle for Sat/Value.
1742 ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputRGB = 1 << 27, // [Input] // ColorEdit, ColorPicker: input and output data in RGB format.
1743 ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputHSV = 1 << 28, // [Input] // ColorEdit, ColorPicker: input and output data in HSV format.
1744
1745 // Defaults Options. You can set application defaults using SetColorEditOptions(). The intent is that you probably don't want to
1746 // override them in most of your calls. Let the user choose via the option menu and/or call SetColorEditOptions() once during startup.
1747 ImGuiColorEditFlags_DefaultOptions_ = ImGuiColorEditFlags_Uint8 | ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayRGB | ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputRGB | ImGuiColorEditFlags_PickerHueBar,
1748
1749 // [Internal] Masks
1750 ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayMask_ = ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayRGB | ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHSV | ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHex,
1751 ImGuiColorEditFlags_DataTypeMask_ = ImGuiColorEditFlags_Uint8 | ImGuiColorEditFlags_Float,
1752 ImGuiColorEditFlags_PickerMask_ = ImGuiColorEditFlags_PickerHueWheel | ImGuiColorEditFlags_PickerHueBar,
1753 ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputMask_ = ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputRGB | ImGuiColorEditFlags_InputHSV
1754
1755 // Obsolete names (will be removed)
1756 // ImGuiColorEditFlags_RGB = ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayRGB, ImGuiColorEditFlags_HSV = ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHSV, ImGuiColorEditFlags_HEX = ImGuiColorEditFlags_DisplayHex // [renamed in 1.69]
1757};

1759// Flags for DragFloat(), DragInt(), SliderFloat(), SliderInt() etc.
1760// We use the same sets of flags for DragXXX() and SliderXXX() functions as the features are the same and it makes it easier to swap them.
1761enum ImGuiSliderFlags_
1762{

1765 ImGuiSliderFlags_Logarithmic = 1 << 5, // Make the widget logarithmic (linear otherwise). Consider using ImGuiSliderFlags_NoRoundToFormat with this if using a format-string with small amount of digits.
1766 ImGuiSliderFlags_NoRoundToFormat = 1 << 6, // Disable rounding underlying value to match precision of the display format string (e.g. %.3f values are rounded to those 3 digits)
1767 ImGuiSliderFlags_NoInput = 1 << 7, // Disable CTRL+Click or Enter key allowing to input text directly into the widget
1768 ImGuiSliderFlags_InvalidMask_ = 0x7000000F // [Internal] We treat using those bits as being potentially a 'float power' argument from the previous API that has got miscast to this enum, and will trigger an assert if needed.

1803// Enumeration for ImGui::SetWindow***(), SetNextWindow***(), SetNextItem***() functions
1804// Represent a condition.
1805// Important: Treat as a regular enum! Do NOT combine multiple values using binary operators! All the functions above treat 0 as a shortcut to ImGuiCond_Always.
1806enum ImGuiCond_
1807{
1808 ImGuiCond_None = 0, // No condition (always set the variable), same as _Always
1809 ImGuiCond_Always = 1 << 0, // No condition (always set the variable)
1810 ImGuiCond_Once = 1 << 1, // Set the variable once per runtime session (only the first call will succeed)
1811 ImGuiCond_FirstUseEver = 1 << 2, // Set the variable if the object/window has no persistently saved data (no entry in .ini file)
1812 ImGuiCond_Appearing = 1 << 3 // Set the variable if the object/window is appearing after being hidden/inactive (or the first time)
1813};

1815//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1816// [SECTION] Helpers: Memory allocations macros, ImVector<>
1817//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1818
1819//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1820// IM_MALLOC(), IM_FREE(), IM_NEW(), IM_PLACEMENT_NEW(), IM_DELETE()
1821// We call C++ constructor on own allocated memory via the placement "new(ptr) Type()" syntax.
1822// Defining a custom placement new() with a custom parameter allows us to bypass including <new> which on some platforms complains when user has disabled exceptions.
1823//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1824
1825struct ImNewWrapper {};
1826inline void* operator new(size_t, ImNewWrapper, void* ptr) { return ptr; }
1827inline void operator delete(void*, ImNewWrapper, void*) {} // This is only required so we can use the symmetrical new()
1828#define IM_ALLOC(_SIZE) ImGui::MemAlloc(_SIZE)
1829#define IM_FREE(_PTR) ImGui::MemFree(_PTR)
1830#define IM_PLACEMENT_NEW(_PTR) new(ImNewWrapper(), _PTR)
1831#define IM_NEW(_TYPE) new(ImNewWrapper(), ImGui::MemAlloc(sizeof(_TYPE))) _TYPE
1832template<typename T> void IM_DELETE(T* p) { if (p) { p->~T(); ImGui::MemFree(p); } }
1833
1834//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1835// ImVector<>
1836// Lightweight std::vector<>-like class to avoid dragging dependencies (also, some implementations of STL with debug enabled are absurdly slow, we bypass it so our code runs fast in debug).
1837//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1838// - You generally do NOT need to care or use this ever. But we need to make it available in imgui.h because some of our public structures are relying on it.
1839// - We use std-like naming convention here, which is a little unusual for this codebase.
1840// - Important: clear() frees memory, resize(0) keep the allocated buffer. We use resize(0) a lot to intentionally recycle allocated buffers across frames and amortize our costs.
1841// - Important: our implementation does NOT call C++ constructors/destructors, we treat everything as raw data! This is intentional but be extra mindful of that,
1842// Do NOT use this class as a std::vector replacement in your own code! Many of the structures used by dear imgui can be safely initialized by a zero-memset.
1843//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1844
1845IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_OFF
1846template<typename T>
1847struct ImVector
1848{
1849 int Size;
1850 int Capacity;
1851 T* Data;
1852
1853 // Provide standard typedefs but we don't use them ourselves.
1854 typedef T value_type;
1855 typedef value_type* iterator;
1856 typedef const value_type* const_iterator;
1857
1858 // Constructors, destructor
1859 inline ImVector() { Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; }
1860 inline ImVector(const ImVector<T>& src) { Size = Capacity = 0; Data = NULL; operator=(src); }
1861 inline ImVector<T>& operator=(const ImVector<T>& src) { clear(); resize(src.Size); memcpy(Data, src.Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(T)); return *this; }
1862 inline ~ImVector() { if (Data) IM_FREE(Data); } // Important: does not destruct anything
1863
1864 inline void clear() { if (Data) { Size = Capacity = 0; IM_FREE(Data); Data = NULL; } } // Important: does not destruct anything
1865 inline void clear_delete() { for (int n = 0; n < Size; n++) IM_DELETE(Data[n]); clear(); } // Important: never called automatically! always explicit.
1866 inline void clear_destruct() { for (int n = 0; n < Size; n++) Data[n].~T(); clear(); } // Important: never called automatically! always explicit.
1867
1868 inline bool empty() const { return Size == 0; }
1869 inline int size() const { return Size; }
1870 inline int size_in_bytes() const { return Size * (int)sizeof(T); }
1871 inline int max_size() const { return 0x7FFFFFFF / (int)sizeof(T); }
1872 inline int capacity() const { return Capacity; }
1873 inline T& operator[](int i) { IM_ASSERT(i >= 0 && i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1874 inline const T& operator[](int i) const { IM_ASSERT(i >= 0 && i < Size); return Data[i]; }
1875
1876 inline T* begin() { return Data; }
1877 inline const T* begin() const { return Data; }
1878 inline T* end() { return Data + Size; }
1879 inline const T* end() const { return Data + Size; }
1880 inline T& front() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1881 inline const T& front() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[0]; }
1882 inline T& back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1883 inline const T& back() const { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); return Data[Size - 1]; }
1884 inline void swap(ImVector<T>& rhs) { int rhs_size = rhs.Size; rhs.Size = Size; Size = rhs_size; int rhs_cap = rhs.Capacity; rhs.Capacity = Capacity; Capacity = rhs_cap; T* rhs_data = rhs.Data; rhs.Data = Data; Data = rhs_data; }
1885
1886 inline int _grow_capacity(int sz) const { int new_capacity = Capacity ? (Capacity + Capacity / 2) : 8; return new_capacity > sz ? new_capacity : sz; }
1887 inline void resize(int new_size) { if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); Size = new_size; }
1888 inline void resize(int new_size, const T& v) { if (new_size > Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(new_size)); if (new_size > Size) for (int n = Size; n < new_size; n++) memcpy(&Data[n], &v, sizeof(v)); Size = new_size; }
1889 inline void shrink(int new_size) { IM_ASSERT(new_size <= Size); Size = new_size; } // Resize a vector to a smaller size, guaranteed not to cause a reallocation
1890 inline void reserve(int new_capacity) { if (new_capacity <= Capacity) return; T* new_data = (T*)IM_ALLOC((size_t)new_capacity * sizeof(T)); if (Data) { memcpy(new_data, Data, (size_t)Size * sizeof(T)); IM_FREE(Data); } Data = new_data; Capacity = new_capacity; }
1891 inline void reserve_discard(int new_capacity) { if (new_capacity <= Capacity) return; if (Data) IM_FREE(Data); Data = (T*)IM_ALLOC((size_t)new_capacity * sizeof(T)); Capacity = new_capacity; }
1892
1893 // NB: It is illegal to call push_back/push_front/insert with a reference pointing inside the ImVector data itself! e.g. v.push_back(v[10]) is forbidden.
1894 inline void push_back(const T& v) { if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); memcpy(&Data[Size], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++; }
1895 inline void pop_back() { IM_ASSERT(Size > 0); Size--; }
1896 inline void push_front(const T& v) { if (Size == 0) push_back(v); else insert(Data, v); }
1897 inline T* erase(const T* it) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + 1, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - 1) * sizeof(T)); Size--; return Data + off; }
1898 inline T* erase(const T* it, const T* it_last){ IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size && it_last >= it && it_last <= Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t count = it_last - it; const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; memmove(Data + off, Data + off + count, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off - (size_t)count) * sizeof(T)); Size -= (int)count; return Data + off; }
1899 inline T* erase_unsorted(const T* it) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (it < Data + Size - 1) memcpy(Data + off, Data + Size - 1, sizeof(T)); Size--; return Data + off; }
1900 inline T* insert(const T* it, const T& v) { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it <= Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; if (Size == Capacity) reserve(_grow_capacity(Size + 1)); if (off < (int)Size) memmove(Data + off + 1, Data + off, ((size_t)Size - (size_t)off) * sizeof(T)); memcpy(&Data[off], &v, sizeof(v)); Size++; return Data + off; }
1901 inline bool contains(const T& v) const { const T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data++ == v) return true; return false; }
1902 inline T* find(const T& v) { T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data == v) break; else ++data; return data; }
1903 inline const T* find(const T& v) const { const T* data = Data; const T* data_end = Data + Size; while (data < data_end) if (*data == v) break; else ++data; return data; }
1904 inline bool find_erase(const T& v) { const T* it = find(v); if (it < Data + Size) { erase(it); return true; } return false; }
1905 inline bool find_erase_unsorted(const T& v) { const T* it = find(v); if (it < Data + Size) { erase_unsorted(it); return true; } return false; }
1906 inline int index_from_ptr(const T* it) const { IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < Data + Size); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; return (int)off; }
1907};
1908IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_RESTORE
1909
1910//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1911// [SECTION] ImGuiStyle
1912//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1913// You may modify the ImGui::GetStyle() main instance during initialization and before NewFrame().
1914// During the frame, use ImGui::PushStyleVar(ImGuiStyleVar_XXXX)/PopStyleVar() to alter the main style values,
1915// and ImGui::PushStyleColor(ImGuiCol_XXX)/PopStyleColor() for colors.
1916//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1917
1918struct ImGuiStyle
1919{
1920 float Alpha; // Global alpha applies to everything in Dear ImGui.
1921 float DisabledAlpha; // Additional alpha multiplier applied by BeginDisabled(). Multiply over current value of Alpha.
1922 ImVec2 WindowPadding; // Padding within a window.
1923 float WindowRounding; // Radius of window corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular windows. Large values tend to lead to variety of artifacts and are not recommended.
1924 float WindowBorderSize; // Thickness of border around windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1925 ImVec2 WindowMinSize; // Minimum window size. This is a global setting. If you want to constraint individual windows, use SetNextWindowSizeConstraints().
1926 ImVec2 WindowTitleAlign; // Alignment for title bar text. Defaults to (0.0f,0.5f) for left-aligned,vertically centered.
1927 ImGuiDir WindowMenuButtonPosition; // Side of the collapsing/docking button in the title bar (None/Left/Right). Defaults to ImGuiDir_Left.
1928 float ChildRounding; // Radius of child window corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular windows.
1929 float ChildBorderSize; // Thickness of border around child windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1930 float PopupRounding; // Radius of popup window corners rounding. (Note that tooltip windows use WindowRounding)
1931 float PopupBorderSize; // Thickness of border around popup/tooltip windows. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1932 ImVec2 FramePadding; // Padding within a framed rectangle (used by most widgets).
1933 float FrameRounding; // Radius of frame corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular frame (used by most widgets).
1934 float FrameBorderSize; // Thickness of border around frames. Generally set to 0.0f or 1.0f. (Other values are not well tested and more CPU/GPU costly).
1935 ImVec2 ItemSpacing; // Horizontal and vertical spacing between widgets/lines.
1936 ImVec2 ItemInnerSpacing; // Horizontal and vertical spacing between within elements of a composed widget (e.g. a slider and its label).
1937 ImVec2 CellPadding; // Padding within a table cell
1938 ImVec2 TouchExtraPadding; // Expand reactive bounding box for touch-based system where touch position is not accurate enough. Unfortunately we don't sort widgets so priority on overlap will always be given to the first widget. So don't grow this too much!
1939 float IndentSpacing; // Horizontal indentation when e.g. entering a tree node. Generally == (FontSize + FramePadding.x*2).
1940 float ColumnsMinSpacing; // Minimum horizontal spacing between two columns. Preferably > (FramePadding.x + 1).
1941 float ScrollbarSize; // Width of the vertical scrollbar, Height of the horizontal scrollbar.
1942 float ScrollbarRounding; // Radius of grab corners for scrollbar.
1943 float GrabMinSize; // Minimum width/height of a grab box for slider/scrollbar.
1944 float GrabRounding; // Radius of grabs corners rounding. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular slider grabs.
1945 float LogSliderDeadzone; // The size in pixels of the dead-zone around zero on logarithmic sliders that cross zero.
1946 float TabRounding; // Radius of upper corners of a tab. Set to 0.0f to have rectangular tabs.
1947 float TabBorderSize; // Thickness of border around tabs.
1948 float TabMinWidthForCloseButton; // Minimum width for close button to appears on an unselected tab when hovered. Set to 0.0f to always show when hovering, set to FLT_MAX to never show close button unless selected.
1949 ImGuiDir ColorButtonPosition; // Side of the color button in the ColorEdit4 widget (left/right). Defaults to ImGuiDir_Right.
1950 ImVec2 ButtonTextAlign; // Alignment of button text when button is larger than text. Defaults to (0.5f, 0.5f) (centered).
1951 ImVec2 SelectableTextAlign; // Alignment of selectable text. Defaults to (0.0f, 0.0f) (top-left aligned). It's generally important to keep this left-aligned if you want to lay multiple items on a same line.
1952 ImVec2 DisplayWindowPadding; // Window position are clamped to be visible within the display area or monitors by at least this amount. Only applies to regular windows.
1953 ImVec2 DisplaySafeAreaPadding; // If you cannot see the edges of your screen (e.g. on a TV) increase the safe area padding. Apply to popups/tooltips as well regular windows. NB: Prefer configuring your TV sets correctly!
1954 float MouseCursorScale; // Scale software rendered mouse cursor (when io.MouseDrawCursor is enabled). We apply per-monitor DPI scaling over this scale. May be removed later.
1955 bool AntiAliasedLines; // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders. Disable if you are really tight on CPU/GPU. Latched at the beginning of the frame (copied to ImDrawList).
1956 bool AntiAliasedLinesUseTex; // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders using textures where possible. Require backend to render with bilinear filtering (NOT point/nearest filtering). Latched at the beginning of the frame (copied to ImDrawList).
1957 bool AntiAliasedFill; // Enable anti-aliased edges around filled shapes (rounded rectangles, circles, etc.). Disable if you are really tight on CPU/GPU. Latched at the beginning of the frame (copied to ImDrawList).
1958 float CurveTessellationTol; // Tessellation tolerance when using PathBezierCurveTo() without a specific number of segments. Decrease for highly tessellated curves (higher quality, more polygons), increase to reduce quality.
1959 float CircleTessellationMaxError; // Maximum error (in pixels) allowed when using AddCircle()/AddCircleFilled() or drawing rounded corner rectangles with no explicit segment count specified. Decrease for higher quality but more geometry.
1960 ImVec4 Colors[ImGuiCol_COUNT];
1961
1962 IMGUI_API ImGuiStyle();
1963 IMGUI_API void ScaleAllSizes(float scale_factor);
1964};

1966//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1967// [SECTION] ImGuiIO
1968//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1969// Communicate most settings and inputs/outputs to Dear ImGui using this structure.
1970// Access via ImGui::GetIO(). Read 'Programmer guide' section in .cpp file for general usage.
1971//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1972
1973// [Internal] Storage used by IsKeyDown(), IsKeyPressed() etc functions.
1974// If prior to 1.87 you used io.KeysDownDuration[] (which was marked as internal), you should use GetKeyData(key)->DownDuration and not io.KeysData[key]->DownDuration.
1975struct ImGuiKeyData
1976{
1977 bool Down; // True for if key is down
1978 float DownDuration; // Duration the key has been down (<0.0f: not pressed, 0.0f: just pressed, >0.0f: time held)
1979 float DownDurationPrev; // Last frame duration the key has been down
1980 float AnalogValue; // 0.0f..1.0f for gamepad values
1981};
1982
1983struct ImGuiIO
1984{
1985 //------------------------------------------------------------------
1986 // Configuration // Default value
1987 //------------------------------------------------------------------
1988
1989 ImGuiConfigFlags ConfigFlags; // = 0 // See ImGuiConfigFlags_ enum. Set by user/application. Gamepad/keyboard navigation options, etc.
1990 ImGuiBackendFlags BackendFlags; // = 0 // See ImGuiBackendFlags_ enum. Set by backend (imgui_impl_xxx files or custom backend) to communicate features supported by the backend.
1991 ImVec2 DisplaySize; // <unset> // Main display size, in pixels (generally == GetMainViewport()->Size). May change every frame.
1992 float DeltaTime; // = 1.0f/60.0f // Time elapsed since last frame, in seconds. May change every frame.
1993 float IniSavingRate; // = 5.0f // Minimum time between saving positions/sizes to .ini file, in seconds.
1994 const char* IniFilename; // = "imgui.ini" // Path to .ini file (important: default "imgui.ini" is relative to current working dir!). Set NULL to disable automatic .ini loading/saving or if you want to manually call LoadIniSettingsXXX() / SaveIniSettingsXXX() functions.
1995 const char* LogFilename; // = "imgui_log.txt"// Path to .log file (default parameter to ImGui::LogToFile when no file is specified).
1996 float MouseDoubleClickTime; // = 0.30f // Time for a double-click, in seconds.
1997 float MouseDoubleClickMaxDist; // = 6.0f // Distance threshold to stay in to validate a double-click, in pixels.
1998 float MouseDragThreshold; // = 6.0f // Distance threshold before considering we are dragging.
1999 float KeyRepeatDelay; // = 0.250f // When holding a key/button, time before it starts repeating, in seconds (for buttons in Repeat mode, etc.).
2000 float KeyRepeatRate; // = 0.050f // When holding a key/button, rate at which it repeats, in seconds.
2001 void* UserData; // = NULL // Store your own data for retrieval by callbacks.
2002
2003 ImFontAtlas*Fonts; // <auto> // Font atlas: load, rasterize and pack one or more fonts into a single texture.
2004 float FontGlobalScale; // = 1.0f // Global scale all fonts
2005 bool FontAllowUserScaling; // = false // Allow user scaling text of individual window with CTRL+Wheel.
2006 ImFont* FontDefault; // = NULL // Font to use on NewFrame(). Use NULL to uses Fonts->Fonts[0].
2007 ImVec2 DisplayFramebufferScale; // = (1, 1) // For retina display or other situations where window coordinates are different from framebuffer coordinates. This generally ends up in ImDrawData::FramebufferScale.
2008
2009 // Docking options (when ImGuiConfigFlags_DockingEnable is set)
2010 bool ConfigDockingNoSplit; // = false // Simplified docking mode: disable window splitting, so docking is limited to merging multiple windows together into tab-bars.
2011 bool ConfigDockingWithShift; // = false // Enable docking with holding Shift key (reduce visual noise, allows dropping in wider space)
2012 bool ConfigDockingAlwaysTabBar; // = false // [BETA] [FIXME: This currently creates regression with auto-sizing and general overhead] Make every single floating window display within a docking node.
2013 bool ConfigDockingTransparentPayload;// = false // [BETA] Make window or viewport transparent when docking and only display docking boxes on the target viewport. Useful if rendering of multiple viewport cannot be synced. Best used with ConfigViewportsNoAutoMerge.
2014
2015 // Viewport options (when ImGuiConfigFlags_ViewportsEnable is set)
2016 bool ConfigViewportsNoAutoMerge; // = false; // Set to make all floating imgui windows always create their own viewport. Otherwise, they are merged into the main host viewports when overlapping it. May also set ImGuiViewportFlags_NoAutoMerge on individual viewport.
2017 bool ConfigViewportsNoTaskBarIcon; // = false // Disable default OS task bar icon flag for secondary viewports. When a viewport doesn't want a task bar icon, ImGuiViewportFlags_NoTaskBarIcon will be set on it.
2018 bool ConfigViewportsNoDecoration; // = true // Disable default OS window decoration flag for secondary viewports. When a viewport doesn't want window decorations, ImGuiViewportFlags_NoDecoration will be set on it. Enabling decoration can create subsequent issues at OS levels (e.g. minimum window size).
2019 bool ConfigViewportsNoDefaultParent; // = false // Disable default OS parenting to main viewport for secondary viewports. By default, viewports are marked with ParentViewportId = <main_viewport>, expecting the platform backend to setup a parent/child relationship between the OS windows (some backend may ignore this). Set to true if you want the default to be 0, then all viewports will be top-level OS windows.
2020
2021 // Miscellaneous options
2022 bool MouseDrawCursor; // = false // Request ImGui to draw a mouse cursor for you (if you are on a platform without a mouse cursor). Cannot be easily renamed to 'io.ConfigXXX' because this is frequently used by backend implementations.
2023 bool ConfigMacOSXBehaviors; // = defined(__APPLE__) // OS X style: Text editing cursor movement using Alt instead of Ctrl, Shortcuts using Cmd/Super instead of Ctrl, Line/Text Start and End using Cmd+Arrows instead of Home/End, Double click selects by word instead of selecting whole text, Multi-selection in lists uses Cmd/Super instead of Ctrl.
2024 bool ConfigInputTrickleEventQueue; // = true // Enable input queue trickling: some types of events submitted during the same frame (e.g. button down + up) will be spread over multiple frames, improving interactions with low framerates.
2025 bool ConfigInputTextCursorBlink; // = true // Enable blinking cursor (optional as some users consider it to be distracting).
2026 bool ConfigInputTextEnterKeepActive; // = false // [BETA] Pressing Enter will keep item active and select contents (single-line only).
2027 bool ConfigDragClickToInputText; // = false // [BETA] Enable turning DragXXX widgets into text input with a simple mouse click-release (without moving). Not desirable on devices without a keyboard.
2028 bool ConfigWindowsResizeFromEdges; // = true // Enable resizing of windows from their edges and from the lower-left corner. This requires (io.BackendFlags & ImGuiBackendFlags_HasMouseCursors) because it needs mouse cursor feedback. (This used to be a per-window ImGuiWindowFlags_ResizeFromAnySide flag)
2029 bool ConfigWindowsMoveFromTitleBarOnly; // = false // Enable allowing to move windows only when clicking on their title bar. Does not apply to windows without a title bar.
2030 float ConfigMemoryCompactTimer; // = 60.0f // Timer (in seconds) to free transient windows/tables memory buffers when unused. Set to -1.0f to disable.

2142 ImVec2 MouseDragMaxDistanceAbs[5]; // Maximum distance, absolute, on each axis, of how much mouse has traveled from the clicking point

2144 float NavInputsDownDuration[ImGuiNavInput_COUNT];
2145 float NavInputsDownDurationPrev[ImGuiNavInput_COUNT];
2146 float PenPressure; // Touch/Pen pressure (0.0f to 1.0f, should be >0.0f only when MouseDown[0] == true). Helper storage currently unused by Dear ImGui.

2161// Shared state of InputText(), passed as an argument to your callback when a ImGuiInputTextFlags_Callback* flag is used.
2162// The callback function should return 0 by default.
2163// Callbacks (follow a flag name and see comments in ImGuiInputTextFlags_ declarations for more details)
2164// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackEdit: Callback on buffer edit (note that InputText() already returns true on edit, the callback is useful mainly to manipulate the underlying buffer while focus is active)
2165// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackAlways: Callback on each iteration
2166// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCompletion: Callback on pressing TAB
2167// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackHistory: Callback on pressing Up/Down arrows
2168// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackCharFilter: Callback on character inputs to replace or discard them. Modify 'EventChar' to replace or discard, or return 1 in callback to discard.
2169// - ImGuiInputTextFlags_CallbackResize: Callback on buffer capacity changes request (beyond 'buf_size' parameter value), allowing the string to grow.
2170struct ImGuiInputTextCallbackData
2171{
2172 ImGuiInputTextFlags EventFlag; // One ImGuiInputTextFlags_Callback* // Read-only
2173 ImGuiInputTextFlags Flags; // What user passed to InputText() // Read-only
2174 void* UserData; // What user passed to InputText() // Read-only
2175
2176 // Arguments for the different callback events
2177 // - To modify the text buffer in a callback, prefer using the InsertChars() / DeleteChars() function. InsertChars() will take care of calling the resize callback if necessary.
2178 // - If you know your edits are not going to resize the underlying buffer allocation, you may modify the contents of 'Buf[]' directly. You need to update 'BufTextLen' accordingly (0 <= BufTextLen < BufSize) and set 'BufDirty'' to true so InputText can update its internal state.
2179 ImWchar EventChar; // Character input // Read-write // [CharFilter] Replace character with another one, or set to zero to drop. return 1 is equivalent to setting EventChar=0;
2180 ImGuiKey EventKey; // Key pressed (Up/Down/TAB) // Read-only // [Completion,History]
2181 char* Buf; // Text buffer // Read-write // [Resize] Can replace pointer / [Completion,History,Always] Only write to pointed data, don't replace the actual pointer!
2182 int BufTextLen; // Text length (in bytes) // Read-write // [Resize,Completion,History,Always] Exclude zero-terminator storage. In C land: == strlen(some_text), in C++ land: string.length()
2183 int BufSize; // Buffer size (in bytes) = capacity+1 // Read-only // [Resize,Completion,History,Always] Include zero-terminator storage. In C land == ARRAYSIZE(my_char_array), in C++ land: string.capacity()+1
2184 bool BufDirty; // Set if you modify Buf/BufTextLen! // Write // [Completion,History,Always]
2185 int CursorPos; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always]
2186 int SelectionStart; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always] == to SelectionEnd when no selection)
2187 int SelectionEnd; // // Read-write // [Completion,History,Always]
2188
2189 // Helper functions for text manipulation.
2190 // Use those function to benefit from the CallbackResize behaviors. Calling those function reset the selection.
2191 IMGUI_API ImGuiInputTextCallbackData();
2192 IMGUI_API void DeleteChars(int pos, int bytes_count);
2193 IMGUI_API void InsertChars(int pos, const char* text, const char* text_end = NULL);
2194 void SelectAll() { SelectionStart = 0; SelectionEnd = BufTextLen; }
2195 void ClearSelection() { SelectionStart = SelectionEnd = BufTextLen; }
2196 bool HasSelection() const { return SelectionStart != SelectionEnd; }
2197};

2199// Resizing callback data to apply custom constraint. As enabled by SetNextWindowSizeConstraints(). Callback is called during the next Begin().
2200// NB: For basic min/max size constraint on each axis you don't need to use the callback! The SetNextWindowSizeConstraints() parameters are enough.
2201struct ImGuiSizeCallbackData
2202{
2203 void* UserData; // Read-only. What user passed to SetNextWindowSizeConstraints()
2204 ImVec2 Pos; // Read-only. Window position, for reference.
2205 ImVec2 CurrentSize; // Read-only. Current window size.
2206 ImVec2 DesiredSize; // Read-write. Desired size, based on user's mouse position. Write to this field to restrain resizing.
2207};

2209// [ALPHA] Rarely used / very advanced uses only. Use with SetNextWindowClass() and DockSpace() functions.
2210// Important: the content of this class is still highly WIP and likely to change and be refactored
2211// before we stabilize Docking features. Please be mindful if using this.
2212// Provide hints:
2213// - To the platform backend via altered viewport flags (enable/disable OS decoration, OS task bar icons, etc.)
2214// - To the platform backend for OS level parent/child relationships of viewport.
2215// - To the docking system for various options and filtering.
2216struct ImGuiWindowClass
2217{
2218 ImGuiID ClassId; // User data. 0 = Default class (unclassed). Windows of different classes cannot be docked with each others.
2219 ImGuiID ParentViewportId; // Hint for the platform backend. -1: use default. 0: request platform backend to not parent the platform. != 0: request platform backend to create a parent<>child relationship between the platform windows. Not conforming backends are free to e.g. parent every viewport to the main viewport or not.
2220 ImGuiViewportFlags ViewportFlagsOverrideSet; // Viewport flags to set when a window of this class owns a viewport. This allows you to enforce OS decoration or task bar icon, override the defaults on a per-window basis.
2221 ImGuiViewportFlags ViewportFlagsOverrideClear; // Viewport flags to clear when a window of this class owns a viewport. This allows you to enforce OS decoration or task bar icon, override the defaults on a per-window basis.
2222 ImGuiTabItemFlags TabItemFlagsOverrideSet; // [EXPERIMENTAL] TabItem flags to set when a window of this class gets submitted into a dock node tab bar. May use with ImGuiTabItemFlags_Leading or ImGuiTabItemFlags_Trailing.
2223 ImGuiDockNodeFlags DockNodeFlagsOverrideSet; // [EXPERIMENTAL] Dock node flags to set when a window of this class is hosted by a dock node (it doesn't have to be selected!)
2224 bool DockingAlwaysTabBar; // Set to true to enforce single floating windows of this class always having their own docking node (equivalent of setting the global io.ConfigDockingAlwaysTabBar)
2225 bool DockingAllowUnclassed; // Set to true to allow windows of this class to be docked/merged with an unclassed window. // FIXME-DOCK: Move to DockNodeFlags override?
2226
2227 ImGuiWindowClass() { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); ParentViewportId = (ImGuiID)-1; DockingAllowUnclassed = true; }
2228};

2263// Sorting specifications for a table (often handling sort specs for a single column, occasionally more)

2288// Helper: Execute a block of code at maximum once a frame. Convenient if you want to quickly create an UI within deep-nested code that runs multiple times every frame.
2289// Usage: static ImGuiOnceUponAFrame oaf; if (oaf) ImGui::Text("This will be called only once per frame");
2290struct ImGuiOnceUponAFrame
2291{
2292 ImGuiOnceUponAFrame() { RefFrame = -1; }
2293 mutable int RefFrame;
2294 operator bool() const { int current_frame = ImGui::GetFrameCount(); if (RefFrame == current_frame) return false; RefFrame = current_frame; return true; }
2295};

2323// Helper: Growable text buffer for logging/accumulating text
2324// (this could be called 'ImGuiTextBuilder' / 'ImGuiStringBuilder')
2325struct ImGuiTextBuffer
2326{
2327 ImVector<char> Buf;
2328 IMGUI_API static char EmptyString[1];
2329
2330 ImGuiTextBuffer() { }
2331 inline char operator[](int i) const { IM_ASSERT(Buf.Data != NULL); return Buf.Data[i]; }
2332 const char* begin() const { return Buf.Data ? &Buf.front() : EmptyString; }
2333 const char* end() const { return Buf.Data ? &Buf.back() : EmptyString; } // Buf is zero-terminated, so end() will point on the zero-terminator
2334 int size() const { return Buf.Size ? Buf.Size - 1 : 0; }
2335 bool empty() const { return Buf.Size <= 1; }
2336 void clear() { Buf.clear(); }
2337 void reserve(int capacity) { Buf.reserve(capacity); }
2338 const char* c_str() const { return Buf.Data ? Buf.Data : EmptyString; }
2339 IMGUI_API void append(const char* str, const char* str_end = NULL);
2340 IMGUI_API void appendf(const char* fmt, ...) IM_FMTARGS(2);
2341 IMGUI_API void appendfv(const char* fmt, va_list args) IM_FMTLIST(2);
2342};

2344// Helper: Key->Value storage
2345// Typically you don't have to worry about this since a storage is held within each Window.
2346// We use it to e.g. store collapse state for a tree (Int 0/1)
2347// This is optimized for efficient lookup (dichotomy into a contiguous buffer) and rare insertion (typically tied to user interactions aka max once a frame)
2348// You can use it as custom user storage for temporary values. Declare your own storage if, for example:
2349// - You want to manipulate the open/close state of a particular sub-tree in your interface (tree node uses Int 0/1 to store their state).
2350// - You want to store custom debug data easily without adding or editing structures in your code (probably not efficient, but convenient)
2351// Types are NOT stored, so it is up to you to make sure your Key don't collide with different types.
2352struct ImGuiStorage
2353{
2354 // [Internal]
2355 struct ImGuiStoragePair
2356 {
2357 ImGuiID key;
2358 union { int val_i; float val_f; void* val_p; };
2359 ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, int _val_i) { key = _key; val_i = _val_i; }
2360 ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, float _val_f) { key = _key; val_f = _val_f; }
2361 ImGuiStoragePair(ImGuiID _key, void* _val_p) { key = _key; val_p = _val_p; }
2362 };
2363
2364 ImVector<ImGuiStoragePair> Data;
2365
2366 // - Get***() functions find pair, never add/allocate. Pairs are sorted so a query is O(log N)
2367 // - Set***() functions find pair, insertion on demand if missing.
2368 // - Sorted insertion is costly, paid once. A typical frame shouldn't need to insert any new pair.
2369 void Clear() { Data.clear(); }
2370 IMGUI_API int GetInt(ImGuiID key, int default_val = 0) const;
2371 IMGUI_API void SetInt(ImGuiID key, int val);
2372 IMGUI_API bool GetBool(ImGuiID key, bool default_val = false) const;
2373 IMGUI_API void SetBool(ImGuiID key, bool val);
2374 IMGUI_API float GetFloat(ImGuiID key, float default_val = 0.0f) const;
2375 IMGUI_API void SetFloat(ImGuiID key, float val);
2376 IMGUI_API void* GetVoidPtr(ImGuiID key) const; // default_val is NULL
2377 IMGUI_API void SetVoidPtr(ImGuiID key, void* val);
2378
2379 // - Get***Ref() functions finds pair, insert on demand if missing, return pointer. Useful if you intend to do Get+Set.
2380 // - References are only valid until a new value is added to the storage. Calling a Set***() function or a Get***Ref() function invalidates the pointer.
2381 // - A typical use case where this is convenient for quick hacking (e.g. add storage during a live Edit&Continue session if you can't modify existing struct)
2382 // float* pvar = ImGui::GetFloatRef(key); ImGui::SliderFloat("var", pvar, 0, 100.0f); some_var += *pvar;
2383 IMGUI_API int* GetIntRef(ImGuiID key, int default_val = 0);
2384 IMGUI_API bool* GetBoolRef(ImGuiID key, bool default_val = false);
2385 IMGUI_API float* GetFloatRef(ImGuiID key, float default_val = 0.0f);
2386 IMGUI_API void** GetVoidPtrRef(ImGuiID key, void* default_val = NULL);
2387
2388 // Use on your own storage if you know only integer are being stored (open/close all tree nodes)
2389 IMGUI_API void SetAllInt(int val);
2390
2391 // For quicker full rebuild of a storage (instead of an incremental one), you may add all your contents and then sort once.
2392 IMGUI_API void BuildSortByKey();
2393};
2394
2395// Helper: Manually clip large list of items.
2396// If you have lots evenly spaced items and you have a random access to the list, you can perform coarse
2397// clipping based on visibility to only submit items that are in view.
2398// The clipper calculates the range of visible items and advance the cursor to compensate for the non-visible items we have skipped.
2399// (Dear ImGui already clip items based on their bounds but: it needs to first layout the item to do so, and generally
2400// fetching/submitting your own data incurs additional cost. Coarse clipping using ImGuiListClipper allows you to easily
2401// scale using lists with tens of thousands of items without a problem)
2402// Usage:
2403// ImGuiListClipper clipper;
2404// clipper.Begin(1000); // We have 1000 elements, evenly spaced.
2405// while (clipper.Step())
2406// for (int i = clipper.DisplayStart; i < clipper.DisplayEnd; i++)
2407// ImGui::Text("line number %d", i);
2408// Generally what happens is:
2409// - Clipper lets you process the first element (DisplayStart = 0, DisplayEnd = 1) regardless of it being visible or not.
2410// - User code submit that one element.
2411// - Clipper can measure the height of the first element
2412// - Clipper calculate the actual range of elements to display based on the current clipping rectangle, position the cursor before the first visible element.
2413// - User code submit visible elements.
2414// - The clipper also handles various subtleties related to keyboard/gamepad navigation, wrapping etc.
2415struct ImGuiListClipper
2416{
2417 int DisplayStart; // First item to display, updated by each call to Step()
2418 int DisplayEnd; // End of items to display (exclusive)
2419 int ItemsCount; // [Internal] Number of items
2420 float ItemsHeight; // [Internal] Height of item after a first step and item submission can calculate it
2421 float StartPosY; // [Internal] Cursor position at the time of Begin() or after table frozen rows are all processed
2422 void* TempData; // [Internal] Internal data
2423
2424 // items_count: Use INT_MAX if you don't know how many items you have (in which case the cursor won't be advanced in the final step)
2425 // items_height: Use -1.0f to be calculated automatically on first step. Otherwise pass in the distance between your items, typically GetTextLineHeightWithSpacing() or GetFrameHeightWithSpacing().
2426 IMGUI_API ImGuiListClipper();
2427 IMGUI_API ~ImGuiListClipper();
2428 IMGUI_API void Begin(int items_count, float items_height = -1.0f);
2429 IMGUI_API void End(); // Automatically called on the last call of Step() that returns false.
2430 IMGUI_API bool Step(); // Call until it returns false. The DisplayStart/DisplayEnd fields will be set and you can process/draw those items.
2431
2432 // Call ForceDisplayRangeByIndices() before first call to Step() if you need a range of items to be displayed regardless of visibility.
2433 IMGUI_API void ForceDisplayRangeByIndices(int item_min, int item_max); // item_max is exclusive e.g. use (42, 42+1) to make item 42 always visible BUT due to alignment/padding of certain items it is likely that an extra item may be included on either end of the display range.
2434
2435#ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
2436 inline ImGuiListClipper(int items_count, float items_height = -1.0f) { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); ItemsCount = -1; Begin(items_count, items_height); } // [removed in 1.79]
2437#endif
2438};
2439
2440// Helpers macros to generate 32-bit encoded colors
2441// User can declare their own format by #defining the 5 _SHIFT/_MASK macros in their imconfig file.
2442#ifndef IM_COL32_R_SHIFT
2443#ifdef IMGUI_USE_BGRA_PACKED_COLOR
2444#define IM_COL32_R_SHIFT 16
2445#define IM_COL32_G_SHIFT 8
2446#define IM_COL32_B_SHIFT 0
2447#define IM_COL32_A_SHIFT 24
2448#define IM_COL32_A_MASK 0xFF000000
2449#else
2450#define IM_COL32_R_SHIFT 0
2451#define IM_COL32_G_SHIFT 8
2452#define IM_COL32_B_SHIFT 16
2453#define IM_COL32_A_SHIFT 24
2454#define IM_COL32_A_MASK 0xFF000000
2455#endif
2456#endif
2457#define IM_COL32(R,G,B,A) (((ImU32)(A)<<IM_COL32_A_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(B)<<IM_COL32_B_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(G)<<IM_COL32_G_SHIFT) | ((ImU32)(R)<<IM_COL32_R_SHIFT))
2458#define IM_COL32_WHITE IM_COL32(255,255,255,255) // Opaque white = 0xFFFFFFFF
2459#define IM_COL32_BLACK IM_COL32(0,0,0,255) // Opaque black
2460#define IM_COL32_BLACK_TRANS IM_COL32(0,0,0,0) // Transparent black = 0x00000000
2461
2462// Helper: ImColor() implicitly converts colors to either ImU32 (packed 4x1 byte) or ImVec4 (4x1 float)
2463// Prefer using IM_COL32() macros if you want a guaranteed compile-time ImU32 for usage with ImDrawList API.
2464// **Avoid storing ImColor! Store either u32 of ImVec4. This is not a full-featured color class. MAY OBSOLETE.
2465// **None of the ImGui API are using ImColor directly but you can use it as a convenience to pass colors in either ImU32 or ImVec4 formats. Explicitly cast to ImU32 or ImVec4 if needed.
2466struct ImColor
2467{
2468 ImVec4 Value;
2469
2470 constexpr ImColor() { }
2471 constexpr ImColor(float r, float g, float b, float a = 1.0f) : Value(r, g, b, a) { }
2472 constexpr ImColor(const ImVec4& col) : Value(col) {}
2473 ImColor(int r, int g, int b, int a = 255) { float sc = 1.0f / 255.0f; Value.x = (float)r * sc; Value.y = (float)g * sc; Value.z = (float)b * sc; Value.w = (float)a * sc; }
2474 ImColor(ImU32 rgba) { float sc = 1.0f / 255.0f; Value.x = (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_R_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * sc; Value.y = (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_G_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * sc; Value.z = (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_B_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * sc; Value.w = (float)((rgba >> IM_COL32_A_SHIFT) & 0xFF) * sc; }
2475 inline operator ImU32() const { return ImGui::ColorConvertFloat4ToU32(Value); }
2476 inline operator ImVec4() const { return Value; }
2477
2478 // FIXME-OBSOLETE: May need to obsolete/cleanup those helpers.
2479 inline void SetHSV(float h, float s, float v, float a = 1.0f){ ImGui::ColorConvertHSVtoRGB(h, s, v, Value.x, Value.y, Value.z); Value.w = a; }
2480 static ImColor HSV(float h, float s, float v, float a = 1.0f) { float r, g, b; ImGui::ColorConvertHSVtoRGB(h, s, v, r, g, b); return ImColor(r, g, b, a); }
2481};
2482
2483//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2484// [SECTION] Drawing API (ImDrawCmd, ImDrawIdx, ImDrawVert, ImDrawChannel, ImDrawListSplitter, ImDrawListFlags, ImDrawList, ImDrawData)
2485// Hold a series of drawing commands. The user provides a renderer for ImDrawData which essentially contains an array of ImDrawList.
2486//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2487
2488// The maximum line width to bake anti-aliased textures for. Build atlas with ImFontAtlasFlags_NoBakedLines to disable baking.
2489#ifndef IM_DRAWLIST_TEX_LINES_WIDTH_MAX
2490#define IM_DRAWLIST_TEX_LINES_WIDTH_MAX (63)
2491#endif
2492
2493// ImDrawCallback: Draw callbacks for advanced uses [configurable type: override in imconfig.h]
2494// NB: You most likely do NOT need to use draw callbacks just to create your own widget or customized UI rendering,
2495// you can poke into the draw list for that! Draw callback may be useful for example to:
2496// A) Change your GPU render state,
2497// B) render a complex 3D scene inside a UI element without an intermediate texture/render target, etc.
2498// The expected behavior from your rendering function is 'if (cmd.UserCallback != NULL) { cmd.UserCallback(parent_list, cmd); } else { RenderTriangles() }'
2499// If you want to override the signature of ImDrawCallback, you can simply use e.g. '#define ImDrawCallback MyDrawCallback' (in imconfig.h) + update rendering backend accordingly.
2500#ifndef ImDrawCallback
2501typedef void (*ImDrawCallback)(const ImDrawList* parent_list, const ImDrawCmd* cmd);
2502#endif
2503
2504// Special Draw callback value to request renderer backend to reset the graphics/render state.
2505// The renderer backend needs to handle this special value, otherwise it will crash trying to call a function at this address.
2506// This is useful for example if you submitted callbacks which you know have altered the render state and you want it to be restored.
2507// It is not done by default because they are many perfectly useful way of altering render state for imgui contents (e.g. changing shader/blending settings before an Image call).
2508#define ImDrawCallback_ResetRenderState (ImDrawCallback)(-1)
2509
2510// Typically, 1 command = 1 GPU draw call (unless command is a callback)
2511// - VtxOffset: When 'io.BackendFlags & ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' is enabled,
2512// this fields allow us to render meshes larger than 64K vertices while keeping 16-bit indices.
2513// Backends made for <1.71. will typically ignore the VtxOffset fields.
2514// - The ClipRect/TextureId/VtxOffset fields must be contiguous as we memcmp() them together (this is asserted for).
2515struct ImDrawCmd
2516{
2517 ImVec4 ClipRect; // 4*4 // Clipping rectangle (x1, y1, x2, y2). Subtract ImDrawData->DisplayPos to get clipping rectangle in "viewport" coordinates
2518 ImTextureID TextureId; // 4-8 // User-provided texture ID. Set by user in ImfontAtlas::SetTexID() for fonts or passed to Image*() functions. Ignore if never using images or multiple fonts atlas.
2519 unsigned int VtxOffset; // 4 // Start offset in vertex buffer. ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset: always 0, otherwise may be >0 to support meshes larger than 64K vertices with 16-bit indices.
2520 unsigned int IdxOffset; // 4 // Start offset in index buffer.
2521 unsigned int ElemCount; // 4 // Number of indices (multiple of 3) to be rendered as triangles. Vertices are stored in the callee ImDrawList's vtx_buffer[] array, indices in idx_buffer[].
2522 ImDrawCallback UserCallback; // 4-8 // If != NULL, call the function instead of rendering the vertices. clip_rect and texture_id will be set normally.
2523 void* UserCallbackData; // 4-8 // The draw callback code can access this.
2524
2525 ImDrawCmd() { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); } // Also ensure our padding fields are zeroed
2526
2527 // Since 1.83: returns ImTextureID associated with this draw call. Warning: DO NOT assume this is always same as 'TextureId' (we will change this function for an upcoming feature)
2528 inline ImTextureID GetTexID() const { return TextureId; }
2529};
2530
2531// Vertex layout
2532#ifndef IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT
2533struct ImDrawVert
2534{
2535 ImVec2 pos;
2536 ImVec2 uv;
2537 ImU32 col;
2538};
2539#else
2540// You can override the vertex format layout by defining IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT in imconfig.h
2541// The code expect ImVec2 pos (8 bytes), ImVec2 uv (8 bytes), ImU32 col (4 bytes), but you can re-order them or add other fields as needed to simplify integration in your engine.
2542// The type has to be described within the macro (you can either declare the struct or use a typedef). This is because ImVec2/ImU32 are likely not declared a the time you'd want to set your type up.
2543// NOTE: IMGUI DOESN'T CLEAR THE STRUCTURE AND DOESN'T CALL A CONSTRUCTOR SO ANY CUSTOM FIELD WILL BE UNINITIALIZED. IF YOU ADD EXTRA FIELDS (SUCH AS A 'Z' COORDINATES) YOU WILL NEED TO CLEAR THEM DURING RENDER OR TO IGNORE THEM.
2544IMGUI_OVERRIDE_DRAWVERT_STRUCT_LAYOUT;
2545#endif
2546
2547// [Internal] For use by ImDrawList
2548struct ImDrawCmdHeader
2549{
2550 ImVec4 ClipRect;
2551 ImTextureID TextureId;
2552 unsigned int VtxOffset;
2553};
2554
2555// [Internal] For use by ImDrawListSplitter
2556struct ImDrawChannel
2557{
2558 ImVector<ImDrawCmd> _CmdBuffer;
2559 ImVector<ImDrawIdx> _IdxBuffer;
2560};

2563// Split/Merge functions are used to split the draw list into different layers which can be drawn into out of order.
2564// This is used by the Columns/Tables API, so items of each column can be batched together in a same draw call.
2565struct ImDrawListSplitter
2566{
2567 int _Current; // Current channel number (0)
2568 int _Count; // Number of active channels (1+)
2569 ImVector<ImDrawChannel> _Channels; // Draw channels (not resized down so _Count might be < Channels.Size)
2570
2571 inline ImDrawListSplitter() { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); }
2572 inline ~ImDrawListSplitter() { ClearFreeMemory(); }
2573 inline void Clear() { _Current = 0; _Count = 1; } // Do not clear Channels[] so our allocations are reused next frame
2574 IMGUI_API void ClearFreeMemory();
2575 IMGUI_API void Split(ImDrawList* draw_list, int count);
2576 IMGUI_API void Merge(ImDrawList* draw_list);
2577 IMGUI_API void SetCurrentChannel(ImDrawList* draw_list, int channel_idx);
2578};
