2580// Flags for ImDrawList functions
2581// (Legacy: bit 0 must always correspond to ImDrawFlags_Closed to be backward compatible with old API using a bool. Bits 1..3 must be unused)
2582enum ImDrawFlags_
2583{
2584 ImDrawFlags_None = 0,
2585 ImDrawFlags_Closed = 1 << 0, // PathStroke(), AddPolyline(): specify that shape should be closed (Important: this is always == 1 for legacy reason)
2586 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft = 1 << 4, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding top-left corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Was 0x01.
2587 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight = 1 << 5, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding top-right corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Was 0x02.
2588 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft = 1 << 6, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding bottom-left corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Was 0x04.
2589 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight = 1 << 7, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): enable rounding bottom-right corner only (when rounding > 0.0f, we default to all corners). Wax 0x08.
2590 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersNone = 1 << 8, // AddRect(), AddRectFilled(), PathRect(): disable rounding on all corners (when rounding > 0.0f). This is NOT zero, NOT an implicit flag!
2591 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTop = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight,
2592 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottom = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight,
2593 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersLeft = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft,
2594 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersRight = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight,
2595 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersAll = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersTopRight | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomLeft | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersBottomRight,
2596 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersDefault_ = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersAll, // Default to ALL corners if none of the _RoundCornersXX flags are specified.
2597 ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersMask_ = ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersAll | ImDrawFlags_RoundCornersNone
2598};
2599
2600// Flags for ImDrawList instance. Those are set automatically by ImGui:: functions from ImGuiIO settings, and generally not manipulated directly.
2601// It is however possible to temporarily alter flags between calls to ImDrawList:: functions.
2602enum ImDrawListFlags_
2603{
2604 ImDrawListFlags_None = 0,
2605 ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedLines = 1 << 0, // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders (*2 the number of triangles for 1.0f wide line or lines thin enough to be drawn using textures, otherwise *3 the number of triangles)
2606 ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedLinesUseTex = 1 << 1, // Enable anti-aliased lines/borders using textures when possible. Require backend to render with bilinear filtering (NOT point/nearest filtering).
2607 ImDrawListFlags_AntiAliasedFill = 1 << 2, // Enable anti-aliased edge around filled shapes (rounded rectangles, circles).
2608 ImDrawListFlags_AllowVtxOffset = 1 << 3 // Can emit 'VtxOffset > 0' to allow large meshes. Set when 'ImGuiBackendFlags_RendererHasVtxOffset' is enabled.
2609};
2610
2611// Draw command list
2612// This is the low-level list of polygons that ImGui:: functions are filling. At the end of the frame,
2613// all command lists are passed to your ImGuiIO::RenderDrawListFn function for rendering.
2614// Each dear imgui window contains its own ImDrawList. You can use ImGui::GetWindowDrawList() to
2615// access the current window draw list and draw custom primitives.
2616// You can interleave normal ImGui:: calls and adding primitives to the current draw list.
2617// In single viewport mode, top-left is == GetMainViewport()->Pos (generally 0,0), bottom-right is == GetMainViewport()->Pos+Size (generally io.DisplaySize).
2618// You are totally free to apply whatever transformation matrix to want to the data (depending on the use of the transformation you may want to apply it to ClipRect as well!)
2619// Important: Primitives are always added to the list and not culled (culling is done at higher-level by ImGui:: functions), if you use this API a lot consider coarse culling your drawn objects.
2620struct ImDrawList
2621{
2622 // This is what you have to render
2623 ImVector<ImDrawCmd> CmdBuffer; // Draw commands. Typically 1 command = 1 GPU draw call, unless the command is a callback.
2624 ImVector<ImDrawIdx> IdxBuffer; // Index buffer. Each command consume ImDrawCmd::ElemCount of those
2625 ImVector<ImDrawVert> VtxBuffer; // Vertex buffer.
2626 ImDrawListFlags Flags; // Flags, you may poke into these to adjust anti-aliasing settings per-primitive.
2627
2628 // [Internal, used while building lists]
2629 unsigned int _VtxCurrentIdx; // [Internal] generally == VtxBuffer.Size unless we are past 64K vertices, in which case this gets reset to 0.
2630 const ImDrawListSharedData* _Data; // Pointer to shared draw data (you can use ImGui::GetDrawListSharedData() to get the one from current ImGui context)
2631 const char* _OwnerName; // Pointer to owner window's name for debugging
2632 ImDrawVert* _VtxWritePtr; // [Internal] point within VtxBuffer.Data after each add command (to avoid using the ImVector<> operators too much)
2633 ImDrawIdx* _IdxWritePtr; // [Internal] point within IdxBuffer.Data after each add command (to avoid using the ImVector<> operators too much)
2634 ImVector<ImVec4> _ClipRectStack; // [Internal]
2635 ImVector<ImTextureID> _TextureIdStack; // [Internal]
2636 ImVector<ImVec2> _Path; // [Internal] current path building
2637 ImDrawCmdHeader _CmdHeader; // [Internal] template of active commands. Fields should match those of CmdBuffer.back().
2638 ImDrawListSplitter _Splitter; // [Internal] for channels api (note: prefer using your own persistent instance of ImDrawListSplitter!)
2639 float _FringeScale; // [Internal] anti-alias fringe is scaled by this value, this helps to keep things sharp while zooming at vertex buffer content
2640
2641 // If you want to create ImDrawList instances, pass them ImGui::GetDrawListSharedData() or create and use your own ImDrawListSharedData (so you can use ImDrawList without ImGui)
2642 ImDrawList(const ImDrawListSharedData* shared_data) { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); _Data = shared_data; }
2643
2644 ~ImDrawList() { _ClearFreeMemory(); }
2645 IMGUI_API void PushClipRect(const ImVec2& clip_rect_min, const ImVec2& clip_rect_max, bool intersect_with_current_clip_rect = false); // Render-level scissoring. This is passed down to your render function but not used for CPU-side coarse clipping. Prefer using higher-level ImGui::PushClipRect() to affect logic (hit-testing and widget culling)
2646 IMGUI_API void PushClipRectFullScreen();
2647 IMGUI_API void PopClipRect();
2648 IMGUI_API void PushTextureID(ImTextureID texture_id);
2649 IMGUI_API void PopTextureID();
2650 inline ImVec2 GetClipRectMin() const { const ImVec4& cr = _ClipRectStack.back(); return ImVec2(cr.x, cr.y); }
2651 inline ImVec2 GetClipRectMax() const { const ImVec4& cr = _ClipRectStack.back(); return ImVec2(cr.z, cr.w); }
2652
2653 // Primitives
2654 // - Filled shapes must always use clockwise winding order. The anti-aliasing fringe depends on it. Counter-clockwise shapes will have "inward" anti-aliasing.
2655 // - For rectangular primitives, "p_min" and "p_max" represent the upper-left and lower-right corners.
2656 // - For circle primitives, use "num_segments == 0" to automatically calculate tessellation (preferred).
2657 // In older versions (until Dear ImGui 1.77) the AddCircle functions defaulted to num_segments == 12.
2658 // In future versions we will use textures to provide cheaper and higher-quality circles.
2659 // Use AddNgon() and AddNgonFilled() functions if you need to guaranteed a specific number of sides.
2660 IMGUI_API void AddLine(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, ImU32 col, float thickness = 1.0f);
2661 IMGUI_API void AddRect(const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, ImU32 col, float rounding = 0.0f, ImDrawFlags flags = 0, float thickness = 1.0f); // a: upper-left, b: lower-right (== upper-left + size)
2662 IMGUI_API void AddRectFilled(const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, ImU32 col, float rounding = 0.0f, ImDrawFlags flags = 0); // a: upper-left, b: lower-right (== upper-left + size)
2663 IMGUI_API void AddRectFilledMultiColor(const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, ImU32 col_upr_left, ImU32 col_upr_right, ImU32 col_bot_right, ImU32 col_bot_left);
2664 IMGUI_API void AddQuad(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col, float thickness = 1.0f);
2665 IMGUI_API void AddQuadFilled(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col);
2666 IMGUI_API void AddTriangle(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, ImU32 col, float thickness = 1.0f);
2667 IMGUI_API void AddTriangleFilled(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, ImU32 col);
2668 IMGUI_API void AddCircle(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments = 0, float thickness = 1.0f);
2669 IMGUI_API void AddCircleFilled(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments = 0);
2670 IMGUI_API void AddNgon(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments, float thickness = 1.0f);
2671 IMGUI_API void AddNgonFilled(const ImVec2& center, float radius, ImU32 col, int num_segments);
2672 IMGUI_API void AddText(const ImVec2& pos, ImU32 col, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end = NULL);
2673 IMGUI_API void AddText(const ImFont* font, float font_size, const ImVec2& pos, ImU32 col, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end = NULL, float wrap_width = 0.0f, const ImVec4* cpu_fine_clip_rect = NULL);
2674 IMGUI_API void AddPolyline(const ImVec2* points, int num_points, ImU32 col, ImDrawFlags flags, float thickness);
2675 IMGUI_API void AddConvexPolyFilled(const ImVec2* points, int num_points, ImU32 col);
2676 IMGUI_API void AddBezierCubic(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col, float thickness, int num_segments = 0); // Cubic Bezier (4 control points)
2677 IMGUI_API void AddBezierQuadratic(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, ImU32 col, float thickness, int num_segments = 0); // Quadratic Bezier (3 control points)
2678
2679 // Image primitives
2680 // - Read FAQ to understand what ImTextureID is.
2681 // - "p_min" and "p_max" represent the upper-left and lower-right corners of the rectangle.
2682 // - "uv_min" and "uv_max" represent the normalized texture coordinates to use for those corners. Using (0,0)->(1,1) texture coordinates will generally display the entire texture.
2683 IMGUI_API void AddImage(ImTextureID user_texture_id, const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, const ImVec2& uv_min = ImVec2(0, 0), const ImVec2& uv_max = ImVec2(1, 1), ImU32 col = IM_COL32_WHITE);
2684 IMGUI_API void AddImageQuad(ImTextureID user_texture_id, const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, const ImVec2& uv1 = ImVec2(0, 0), const ImVec2& uv2 = ImVec2(1, 0), const ImVec2& uv3 = ImVec2(1, 1), const ImVec2& uv4 = ImVec2(0, 1), ImU32 col = IM_COL32_WHITE);
2685 IMGUI_API void AddImageRounded(ImTextureID user_texture_id, const ImVec2& p_min, const ImVec2& p_max, const ImVec2& uv_min, const ImVec2& uv_max, ImU32 col, float rounding, ImDrawFlags flags = 0);
2686
2687 // Stateful path API, add points then finish with PathFillConvex() or PathStroke()
2688 // - Filled shapes must always use clockwise winding order. The anti-aliasing fringe depends on it. Counter-clockwise shapes will have "inward" anti-aliasing.
2689 inline void PathClear() { _Path.Size = 0; }
2690 inline void PathLineTo(const ImVec2& pos) { _Path.push_back(pos); }
2691 inline void PathLineToMergeDuplicate(const ImVec2& pos) { if (_Path.Size == 0 || memcmp(&_Path.Data[_Path.Size - 1], &pos, 8) != 0) _Path.push_back(pos); }
2692 inline void PathFillConvex(ImU32 col) { AddConvexPolyFilled(_Path.Data, _Path.Size, col); _Path.Size = 0; }
2693 inline void PathStroke(ImU32 col, ImDrawFlags flags = 0, float thickness = 1.0f) { AddPolyline(_Path.Data, _Path.Size, col, flags, thickness); _Path.Size = 0; }
2694 IMGUI_API void PathArcTo(const ImVec2& center, float radius, float a_min, float a_max, int num_segments = 0);
2695 IMGUI_API void PathArcToFast(const ImVec2& center, float radius, int a_min_of_12, int a_max_of_12); // Use precomputed angles for a 12 steps circle
2696 IMGUI_API void PathBezierCubicCurveTo(const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, int num_segments = 0); // Cubic Bezier (4 control points)
2697 IMGUI_API void PathBezierQuadraticCurveTo(const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, int num_segments = 0); // Quadratic Bezier (3 control points)
2698 IMGUI_API void PathRect(const ImVec2& rect_min, const ImVec2& rect_max, float rounding = 0.0f, ImDrawFlags flags = 0);
2699
2700 // Advanced
2701 IMGUI_API void AddCallback(ImDrawCallback callback, void* callback_data); // Your rendering function must check for 'UserCallback' in ImDrawCmd and call the function instead of rendering triangles.
2702 IMGUI_API void AddDrawCmd(); // This is useful if you need to forcefully create a new draw call (to allow for dependent rendering / blending). Otherwise primitives are merged into the same draw-call as much as possible
2703 IMGUI_API ImDrawList* CloneOutput() const; // Create a clone of the CmdBuffer/IdxBuffer/VtxBuffer.
2704
2705 // Advanced: Channels
2706 // - Use to split render into layers. By switching channels to can render out-of-order (e.g. submit FG primitives before BG primitives)
2707 // - Use to minimize draw calls (e.g. if going back-and-forth between multiple clipping rectangles, prefer to append into separate channels then merge at the end)
2708 // - FIXME-OBSOLETE: This API shouldn't have been in ImDrawList in the first place!
2709 // Prefer using your own persistent instance of ImDrawListSplitter as you can stack them.
2710 // Using the ImDrawList::ChannelsXXXX you cannot stack a split over another.
2711 inline void ChannelsSplit(int count) { _Splitter.Split(this, count); }
2712 inline void ChannelsMerge() { _Splitter.Merge(this); }
2713 inline void ChannelsSetCurrent(int n) { _Splitter.SetCurrentChannel(this, n); }
2714
2715 // Advanced: Primitives allocations
2716 // - We render triangles (three vertices)
2717 // - All primitives needs to be reserved via PrimReserve() beforehand.
2718 IMGUI_API void PrimReserve(int idx_count, int vtx_count);
2719 IMGUI_API void PrimUnreserve(int idx_count, int vtx_count);
2720 IMGUI_API void PrimRect(const ImVec2& a, const ImVec2& b, ImU32 col); // Axis aligned rectangle (composed of two triangles)
2721 IMGUI_API void PrimRectUV(const ImVec2& a, const ImVec2& b, const ImVec2& uv_a, const ImVec2& uv_b, ImU32 col);
2722 IMGUI_API void PrimQuadUV(const ImVec2& a, const ImVec2& b, const ImVec2& c, const ImVec2& d, const ImVec2& uv_a, const ImVec2& uv_b, const ImVec2& uv_c, const ImVec2& uv_d, ImU32 col);
2723 inline void PrimWriteVtx(const ImVec2& pos, const ImVec2& uv, ImU32 col) { _VtxWritePtr->pos = pos; _VtxWritePtr->uv = uv; _VtxWritePtr->col = col; _VtxWritePtr++; _VtxCurrentIdx++; }
2724 inline void PrimWriteIdx(ImDrawIdx idx) { *_IdxWritePtr = idx; _IdxWritePtr++; }
2725 inline void PrimVtx(const ImVec2& pos, const ImVec2& uv, ImU32 col) { PrimWriteIdx((ImDrawIdx)_VtxCurrentIdx); PrimWriteVtx(pos, uv, col); } // Write vertex with unique index
2726
2727#ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
2728 inline void AddBezierCurve(const ImVec2& p1, const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, ImU32 col, float thickness, int num_segments = 0) { AddBezierCubic(p1, p2, p3, p4, col, thickness, num_segments); } // OBSOLETED in 1.80 (Jan 2021)
2729 inline void PathBezierCurveTo(const ImVec2& p2, const ImVec2& p3, const ImVec2& p4, int num_segments = 0) { PathBezierCubicCurveTo(p2, p3, p4, num_segments); } // OBSOLETED in 1.80 (Jan 2021)
2730#endif
2731
2732 // [Internal helpers]
2733 IMGUI_API void _ResetForNewFrame();
2734 IMGUI_API void _ClearFreeMemory();
2735 IMGUI_API void _PopUnusedDrawCmd();
2736 IMGUI_API void _TryMergeDrawCmds();
2737 IMGUI_API void _OnChangedClipRect();
2738 IMGUI_API void _OnChangedTextureID();
2739 IMGUI_API void _OnChangedVtxOffset();
2740 IMGUI_API int _CalcCircleAutoSegmentCount(float radius) const;
2741 IMGUI_API void _PathArcToFastEx(const ImVec2& center, float radius, int a_min_sample, int a_max_sample, int a_step);
2742 IMGUI_API void _PathArcToN(const ImVec2& center, float radius, float a_min, float a_max, int num_segments);
2743};

2745// All draw data to render a Dear ImGui frame
2746// (NB: the style and the naming convention here is a little inconsistent, we currently preserve them for backward compatibility purpose,
2747// as this is one of the oldest structure exposed by the library! Basically, ImDrawList == CmdList)
2748struct ImDrawData
2749{
2750 bool Valid; // Only valid after Render() is called and before the next NewFrame() is called.
2751 int CmdListsCount; // Number of ImDrawList* to render
2752 int TotalIdxCount; // For convenience, sum of all ImDrawList's IdxBuffer.Size
2753 int TotalVtxCount; // For convenience, sum of all ImDrawList's VtxBuffer.Size
2754 ImDrawList** CmdLists; // Array of ImDrawList* to render. The ImDrawList are owned by ImGuiContext and only pointed to from here.
2755 ImVec2 DisplayPos; // Top-left position of the viewport to render (== top-left of the orthogonal projection matrix to use) (== GetMainViewport()->Pos for the main viewport, == (0.0) in most single-viewport applications)
2756 ImVec2 DisplaySize; // Size of the viewport to render (== GetMainViewport()->Size for the main viewport, == io.DisplaySize in most single-viewport applications)
2757 ImVec2 FramebufferScale; // Amount of pixels for each unit of DisplaySize. Based on io.DisplayFramebufferScale. Generally (1,1) on normal display, (2,2) on OSX with Retina display.
2758 ImGuiViewport* OwnerViewport; // Viewport carrying the ImDrawData instance, might be of use to the renderer (generally not).
2759
2760 // Functions
2761 ImDrawData() { Clear(); }
2762 void Clear() { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); } // The ImDrawList are owned by ImGuiContext!
2763 IMGUI_API void DeIndexAllBuffers(); // Helper to convert all buffers from indexed to non-indexed, in case you cannot render indexed. Note: this is slow and most likely a waste of resources. Always prefer indexed rendering!
2764 IMGUI_API void ScaleClipRects(const ImVec2& fb_scale); // Helper to scale the ClipRect field of each ImDrawCmd. Use if your final output buffer is at a different scale than Dear ImGui expects, or if there is a difference between your window resolution and framebuffer resolution.
2765};

2767//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2768// [SECTION] Font API (ImFontConfig, ImFontGlyph, ImFontAtlasFlags, ImFontAtlas, ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder, ImFont)
2769//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2770
2771struct ImFontConfig
2772{
2773 void* FontData; // // TTF/OTF data
2774 int FontDataSize; // // TTF/OTF data size
2775 bool FontDataOwnedByAtlas; // true // TTF/OTF data ownership taken by the container ImFontAtlas (will delete memory itself).
2776 int FontNo; // 0 // Index of font within TTF/OTF file
2777 float SizePixels; // // Size in pixels for rasterizer (more or less maps to the resulting font height).
2778 int OversampleH; // 3 // Rasterize at higher quality for sub-pixel positioning. Note the difference between 2 and 3 is minimal so you can reduce this to 2 to save memory. Read https://github.com/nothings/stb/blob/master/tests/oversample/README.md for details.
2779 int OversampleV; // 1 // Rasterize at higher quality for sub-pixel positioning. This is not really useful as we don't use sub-pixel positions on the Y axis.
2780 bool PixelSnapH; // false // Align every glyph to pixel boundary. Useful e.g. if you are merging a non-pixel aligned font with the default font. If enabled, you can set OversampleH/V to 1.
2781 ImVec2 GlyphExtraSpacing; // 0, 0 // Extra spacing (in pixels) between glyphs. Only X axis is supported for now.
2782 ImVec2 GlyphOffset; // 0, 0 // Offset all glyphs from this font input.
2783 const ImWchar* GlyphRanges; // NULL // Pointer to a user-provided list of Unicode range (2 value per range, values are inclusive, zero-terminated list). THE ARRAY DATA NEEDS TO PERSIST AS LONG AS THE FONT IS ALIVE.
2784 float GlyphMinAdvanceX; // 0 // Minimum AdvanceX for glyphs, set Min to align font icons, set both Min/Max to enforce mono-space font
2785 float GlyphMaxAdvanceX; // FLT_MAX // Maximum AdvanceX for glyphs
2786 bool MergeMode; // false // Merge into previous ImFont, so you can combine multiple inputs font into one ImFont (e.g. ASCII font + icons + Japanese glyphs). You may want to use GlyphOffset.y when merge font of different heights.
2787 unsigned int FontBuilderFlags; // 0 // Settings for custom font builder. THIS IS BUILDER IMPLEMENTATION DEPENDENT. Leave as zero if unsure.
2788 float RasterizerMultiply; // 1.0f // Brighten (>1.0f) or darken (<1.0f) font output. Brightening small fonts may be a good workaround to make them more readable.
2789 ImWchar EllipsisChar; // -1 // Explicitly specify unicode codepoint of ellipsis character. When fonts are being merged first specified ellipsis will be used.
2790
2791 // [Internal]
2792 char Name[40]; // Name (strictly to ease debugging)
2793 ImFont* DstFont;
2794
2795 IMGUI_API ImFontConfig();
2796};
2797
2798// Hold rendering data for one glyph.
2799// (Note: some language parsers may fail to convert the 31+1 bitfield members, in this case maybe drop store a single u32 or we can rework this)
2800struct ImFontGlyph
2801{
2802 unsigned int Colored : 1; // Flag to indicate glyph is colored and should generally ignore tinting (make it usable with no shift on little-endian as this is used in loops)
2803 unsigned int Visible : 1; // Flag to indicate glyph has no visible pixels (e.g. space). Allow early out when rendering.
2804 unsigned int Codepoint : 30; // 0x0000..0x10FFFF
2805 float AdvanceX; // Distance to next character (= data from font + ImFontConfig::GlyphExtraSpacing.x baked in)
2806 float X0, Y0, X1, Y1; // Glyph corners
2807 float U0, V0, U1, V1; // Texture coordinates
2808};
2809
2810// Helper to build glyph ranges from text/string data. Feed your application strings/characters to it then call BuildRanges().
2811// This is essentially a tightly packed of vector of 64k booleans = 8KB storage.
2812struct ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder
2813{
2814 ImVector<ImU32> UsedChars; // Store 1-bit per Unicode code point (0=unused, 1=used)
2815
2816 ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder() { Clear(); }
2817 inline void Clear() { int size_in_bytes = (IM_UNICODE_CODEPOINT_MAX + 1) / 8; UsedChars.resize(size_in_bytes / (int)sizeof(ImU32)); memset(UsedChars.Data, 0, (size_t)size_in_bytes); }
2818 inline bool GetBit(size_t n) const { int off = (int)(n >> 5); ImU32 mask = 1u << (n & 31); return (UsedChars[off] & mask) != 0; } // Get bit n in the array
2819 inline void SetBit(size_t n) { int off = (int)(n >> 5); ImU32 mask = 1u << (n & 31); UsedChars[off] |= mask; } // Set bit n in the array
2820 inline void AddChar(ImWchar c) { SetBit(c); } // Add character
2821 IMGUI_API void AddText(const char* text, const char* text_end = NULL); // Add string (each character of the UTF-8 string are added)
2822 IMGUI_API void AddRanges(const ImWchar* ranges); // Add ranges, e.g. builder.AddRanges(ImFontAtlas::GetGlyphRangesDefault()) to force add all of ASCII/Latin+Ext
2823 IMGUI_API void BuildRanges(ImVector<ImWchar>* out_ranges); // Output new ranges
2824};
2825
2826// See ImFontAtlas::AddCustomRectXXX functions.
2827struct ImFontAtlasCustomRect
2828{
2829 unsigned short Width, Height; // Input // Desired rectangle dimension
2830 unsigned short X, Y; // Output // Packed position in Atlas
2831 unsigned int GlyphID; // Input // For custom font glyphs only (ID < 0x110000)
2832 float GlyphAdvanceX; // Input // For custom font glyphs only: glyph xadvance
2833 ImVec2 GlyphOffset; // Input // For custom font glyphs only: glyph display offset
2834 ImFont* Font; // Input // For custom font glyphs only: target font
2835 ImFontAtlasCustomRect() { Width = Height = 0; X = Y = 0xFFFF; GlyphID = 0; GlyphAdvanceX = 0.0f; GlyphOffset = ImVec2(0, 0); Font = NULL; }
2836 bool IsPacked() const { return X != 0xFFFF; }
2837};
2838
2839// Flags for ImFontAtlas build
2840enum ImFontAtlasFlags_
2841{
2842 ImFontAtlasFlags_None = 0,
2843 ImFontAtlasFlags_NoPowerOfTwoHeight = 1 << 0, // Don't round the height to next power of two
2844 ImFontAtlasFlags_NoMouseCursors = 1 << 1, // Don't build software mouse cursors into the atlas (save a little texture memory)
2845 ImFontAtlasFlags_NoBakedLines = 1 << 2 // Don't build thick line textures into the atlas (save a little texture memory, allow support for point/nearest filtering). The AntiAliasedLinesUseTex features uses them, otherwise they will be rendered using polygons (more expensive for CPU/GPU).
2846};
2847
2848// Load and rasterize multiple TTF/OTF fonts into a same texture. The font atlas will build a single texture holding:
2849// - One or more fonts.
2850// - Custom graphics data needed to render the shapes needed by Dear ImGui.
2851// - Mouse cursor shapes for software cursor rendering (unless setting 'Flags |= ImFontAtlasFlags_NoMouseCursors' in the font atlas).
2852// It is the user-code responsibility to setup/build the atlas, then upload the pixel data into a texture accessible by your graphics api.
2853// - Optionally, call any of the AddFont*** functions. If you don't call any, the default font embedded in the code will be loaded for you.
2854// - Call GetTexDataAsAlpha8() or GetTexDataAsRGBA32() to build and retrieve pixels data.
2855// - Upload the pixels data into a texture within your graphics system (see imgui_impl_xxxx.cpp examples)
2856// - Call SetTexID(my_tex_id); and pass the pointer/identifier to your texture in a format natural to your graphics API.
2857// This value will be passed back to you during rendering to identify the texture. Read FAQ entry about ImTextureID for more details.
2858// Common pitfalls:
2859// - If you pass a 'glyph_ranges' array to AddFont*** functions, you need to make sure that your array persist up until the
2860// atlas is build (when calling GetTexData*** or Build()). We only copy the pointer, not the data.
2861// - Important: By default, AddFontFromMemoryTTF() takes ownership of the data. Even though we are not writing to it, we will free the pointer on destruction.
2862// You can set font_cfg->FontDataOwnedByAtlas=false to keep ownership of your data and it won't be freed,
2863// - Even though many functions are suffixed with "TTF", OTF data is supported just as well.
2864// - This is an old API and it is currently awkward for those and and various other reasons! We will address them in the future!
2865struct ImFontAtlas
2866{
2867 IMGUI_API ImFontAtlas();
2868 IMGUI_API ~ImFontAtlas();
2869 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFont(const ImFontConfig* font_cfg);
2870 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontDefault(const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL);
2871 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromFileTTF(const char* filename, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL);
2872 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromMemoryTTF(void* font_data, int font_size, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL); // Note: Transfer ownership of 'ttf_data' to ImFontAtlas! Will be deleted after destruction of the atlas. Set font_cfg->FontDataOwnedByAtlas=false to keep ownership of your data and it won't be freed.
2873 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromMemoryCompressedTTF(const void* compressed_font_data, int compressed_font_size, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL); // 'compressed_font_data' still owned by caller. Compress with binary_to_compressed_c.cpp.
2874 IMGUI_API ImFont* AddFontFromMemoryCompressedBase85TTF(const char* compressed_font_data_base85, float size_pixels, const ImFontConfig* font_cfg = NULL, const ImWchar* glyph_ranges = NULL); // 'compressed_font_data_base85' still owned by caller. Compress with binary_to_compressed_c.cpp with -base85 parameter.
2875 IMGUI_API void ClearInputData(); // Clear input data (all ImFontConfig structures including sizes, TTF data, glyph ranges, etc.) = all the data used to build the texture and fonts.
2876 IMGUI_API void ClearTexData(); // Clear output texture data (CPU side). Saves RAM once the texture has been copied to graphics memory.
2877 IMGUI_API void ClearFonts(); // Clear output font data (glyphs storage, UV coordinates).
2878 IMGUI_API void Clear(); // Clear all input and output.
2879
2880 // Build atlas, retrieve pixel data.
2881 // User is in charge of copying the pixels into graphics memory (e.g. create a texture with your engine). Then store your texture handle with SetTexID().
2882 // The pitch is always = Width * BytesPerPixels (1 or 4)
2883 // Building in RGBA32 format is provided for convenience and compatibility, but note that unless you manually manipulate or copy color data into
2884 // the texture (e.g. when using the AddCustomRect*** api), then the RGB pixels emitted will always be white (~75% of memory/bandwidth waste.
2885 IMGUI_API bool Build(); // Build pixels data. This is called automatically for you by the GetTexData*** functions.
2886 IMGUI_API void GetTexDataAsAlpha8(unsigned char** out_pixels, int* out_width, int* out_height, int* out_bytes_per_pixel = NULL); // 1 byte per-pixel
2887 IMGUI_API void GetTexDataAsRGBA32(unsigned char** out_pixels, int* out_width, int* out_height, int* out_bytes_per_pixel = NULL); // 4 bytes-per-pixel
2888 bool IsBuilt() const { return Fonts.Size > 0 && TexReady; } // Bit ambiguous: used to detect when user didn't built texture but effectively we should check TexID != 0 except that would be backend dependent...
2889 void SetTexID(ImTextureID id) { TexID = id; }
2890
2891 //-------------------------------------------
2892 // Glyph Ranges
2893 //-------------------------------------------
2894
2895 // Helpers to retrieve list of common Unicode ranges (2 value per range, values are inclusive, zero-terminated list)
2896 // NB: Make sure that your string are UTF-8 and NOT in your local code page. In C++11, you can create UTF-8 string literal using the u8"Hello world" syntax. See FAQ for details.
2897 // NB: Consider using ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder to build glyph ranges from textual data.
2898 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesDefault(); // Basic Latin, Extended Latin
2899 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesKorean(); // Default + Korean characters
2900 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesJapanese(); // Default + Hiragana, Katakana, Half-Width, Selection of 2999 Ideographs
2901 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesChineseFull(); // Default + Half-Width + Japanese Hiragana/Katakana + full set of about 21000 CJK Unified Ideographs
2902 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesChineseSimplifiedCommon();// Default + Half-Width + Japanese Hiragana/Katakana + set of 2500 CJK Unified Ideographs for common simplified Chinese
2903 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesCyrillic(); // Default + about 400 Cyrillic characters
2904 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesThai(); // Default + Thai characters
2905 IMGUI_API const ImWchar* GetGlyphRangesVietnamese(); // Default + Vietnamese characters
2906
2907 //-------------------------------------------
2908 // [BETA] Custom Rectangles/Glyphs API
2909 //-------------------------------------------
2910
2911 // You can request arbitrary rectangles to be packed into the atlas, for your own purposes.
2912 // - After calling Build(), you can query the rectangle position and render your pixels.
2913 // - If you render colored output, set 'atlas->TexPixelsUseColors = true' as this may help some backends decide of prefered texture format.
2914 // - You can also request your rectangles to be mapped as font glyph (given a font + Unicode point),
2915 // so you can render e.g. custom colorful icons and use them as regular glyphs.
2916 // - Read docs/FONTS.md for more details about using colorful icons.
2917 // - Note: this API may be redesigned later in order to support multi-monitor varying DPI settings.
2918 IMGUI_API int AddCustomRectRegular(int width, int height);
2919 IMGUI_API int AddCustomRectFontGlyph(ImFont* font, ImWchar id, int width, int height, float advance_x, const ImVec2& offset = ImVec2(0, 0));
2920 ImFontAtlasCustomRect* GetCustomRectByIndex(int index) { IM_ASSERT(index >= 0); return &CustomRects[index]; }
2921
2922 // [Internal]
2923 IMGUI_API void CalcCustomRectUV(const ImFontAtlasCustomRect* rect, ImVec2* out_uv_min, ImVec2* out_uv_max) const;
2924 IMGUI_API bool GetMouseCursorTexData(ImGuiMouseCursor cursor, ImVec2* out_offset, ImVec2* out_size, ImVec2 out_uv_border[2], ImVec2 out_uv_fill[2]);
2925
2926 //-------------------------------------------
2927 // Members
2928 //-------------------------------------------
2929
2930 ImFontAtlasFlags Flags; // Build flags (see ImFontAtlasFlags_)
2931 ImTextureID TexID; // User data to refer to the texture once it has been uploaded to user's graphic systems. It is passed back to you during rendering via the ImDrawCmd structure.
2932 int TexDesiredWidth; // Texture width desired by user before Build(). Must be a power-of-two. If have many glyphs your graphics API have texture size restrictions you may want to increase texture width to decrease height.
2933 int TexGlyphPadding; // Padding between glyphs within texture in pixels. Defaults to 1. If your rendering method doesn't rely on bilinear filtering you may set this to 0 (will also need to set AntiAliasedLinesUseTex = false).
2934 bool Locked; // Marked as Locked by ImGui::NewFrame() so attempt to modify the atlas will assert.
2935
2936 // [Internal]
2937 // NB: Access texture data via GetTexData*() calls! Which will setup a default font for you.
2938 bool TexReady; // Set when texture was built matching current font input
2939 bool TexPixelsUseColors; // Tell whether our texture data is known to use colors (rather than just alpha channel), in order to help backend select a format.
2940 unsigned char* TexPixelsAlpha8; // 1 component per pixel, each component is unsigned 8-bit. Total size = TexWidth * TexHeight
2941 unsigned int* TexPixelsRGBA32; // 4 component per pixel, each component is unsigned 8-bit. Total size = TexWidth * TexHeight * 4
2942 int TexWidth; // Texture width calculated during Build().
2943 int TexHeight; // Texture height calculated during Build().
2944 ImVec2 TexUvScale; // = (1.0f/TexWidth, 1.0f/TexHeight)
2945 ImVec2 TexUvWhitePixel; // Texture coordinates to a white pixel
2946 ImVector<ImFont*> Fonts; // Hold all the fonts returned by AddFont*. Fonts[0] is the default font upon calling ImGui::NewFrame(), use ImGui::PushFont()/PopFont() to change the current font.
2947 ImVector<ImFontAtlasCustomRect> CustomRects; // Rectangles for packing custom texture data into the atlas.
2948 ImVector<ImFontConfig> ConfigData; // Configuration data
2949 ImVec4 TexUvLines[IM_DRAWLIST_TEX_LINES_WIDTH_MAX + 1]; // UVs for baked anti-aliased lines
2950
2951 // [Internal] Font builder
2952 const ImFontBuilderIO* FontBuilderIO; // Opaque interface to a font builder (default to stb_truetype, can be changed to use FreeType by defining IMGUI_ENABLE_FREETYPE).
2953 unsigned int FontBuilderFlags; // Shared flags (for all fonts) for custom font builder. THIS IS BUILD IMPLEMENTATION DEPENDENT. Per-font override is also available in ImFontConfig.
2954
2955 // [Internal] Packing data
2956 int PackIdMouseCursors; // Custom texture rectangle ID for white pixel and mouse cursors
2957 int PackIdLines; // Custom texture rectangle ID for baked anti-aliased lines
2958

2960 //typedef ImFontAtlasCustomRect CustomRect; // OBSOLETED in 1.72+
2961 //typedef ImFontGlyphRangesBuilder GlyphRangesBuilder; // OBSOLETED in 1.67+
2962};

2964// Font runtime data and rendering
2965// ImFontAtlas automatically loads a default embedded font for you when you call GetTexDataAsAlpha8() or GetTexDataAsRGBA32().
2966struct ImFont
2967{
2968 // Members: Hot ~20/24 bytes (for CalcTextSize)
2969 ImVector<float> IndexAdvanceX; // 12-16 // out // // Sparse. Glyphs->AdvanceX in a directly indexable way (cache-friendly for CalcTextSize functions which only this this info, and are often bottleneck in large UI).
2970 float FallbackAdvanceX; // 4 // out // = FallbackGlyph->AdvanceX
2971 float FontSize; // 4 // in // // Height of characters/line, set during loading (don't change after loading)
2972
2973 // Members: Hot ~28/40 bytes (for CalcTextSize + render loop)
2974 ImVector<ImWchar> IndexLookup; // 12-16 // out // // Sparse. Index glyphs by Unicode code-point.
2975 ImVector<ImFontGlyph> Glyphs; // 12-16 // out // // All glyphs.
2976 const ImFontGlyph* FallbackGlyph; // 4-8 // out // = FindGlyph(FontFallbackChar)
2977
2978 // Members: Cold ~32/40 bytes
2979 ImFontAtlas* ContainerAtlas; // 4-8 // out // // What we has been loaded into
2980 const ImFontConfig* ConfigData; // 4-8 // in // // Pointer within ContainerAtlas->ConfigData
2981 short ConfigDataCount; // 2 // in // ~ 1 // Number of ImFontConfig involved in creating this font. Bigger than 1 when merging multiple font sources into one ImFont.
2982 ImWchar FallbackChar; // 2 // out // = FFFD/'?' // Character used if a glyph isn't found.
2983 ImWchar EllipsisChar; // 2 // out // = '...' // Character used for ellipsis rendering.
2984 ImWchar DotChar; // 2 // out // = '.' // Character used for ellipsis rendering (if a single '...' character isn't found)
2985 bool DirtyLookupTables; // 1 // out //
2986 float Scale; // 4 // in // = 1.f // Base font scale, multiplied by the per-window font scale which you can adjust with SetWindowFontScale()
2987 float Ascent, Descent; // 4+4 // out // // Ascent: distance from top to bottom of e.g. 'A' [0..FontSize]
2988 int MetricsTotalSurface;// 4 // out // // Total surface in pixels to get an idea of the font rasterization/texture cost (not exact, we approximate the cost of padding between glyphs)
2989 ImU8 Used4kPagesMap[(IM_UNICODE_CODEPOINT_MAX+1)/4096/8]; // 2 bytes if ImWchar=ImWchar16, 34 bytes if ImWchar==ImWchar32. Store 1-bit for each block of 4K codepoints that has one active glyph. This is mainly used to facilitate iterations across all used codepoints.
2990
2991 // Methods
2992 IMGUI_API ImFont();
2993 IMGUI_API ~ImFont();
2994 IMGUI_API const ImFontGlyph*FindGlyph(ImWchar c) const;
2995 IMGUI_API const ImFontGlyph*FindGlyphNoFallback(ImWchar c) const;
2996 float GetCharAdvance(ImWchar c) const { return ((int)c < IndexAdvanceX.Size) ? IndexAdvanceX[(int)c] : FallbackAdvanceX; }
2997 bool IsLoaded() const { return ContainerAtlas != NULL; }
2998 const char* GetDebugName() const { return ConfigData ? ConfigData->Name : "<unknown>"; }
2999
3000 // 'max_width' stops rendering after a certain width (could be turned into a 2d size). FLT_MAX to disable.
3001 // 'wrap_width' enable automatic word-wrapping across multiple lines to fit into given width. 0.0f to disable.
3002 IMGUI_API ImVec2 CalcTextSizeA(float size, float max_width, float wrap_width, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end = NULL, const char** remaining = NULL) const; // utf8
3003 IMGUI_API const char* CalcWordWrapPositionA(float scale, const char* text, const char* text_end, float wrap_width) const;
3004 IMGUI_API void RenderChar(ImDrawList* draw_list, float size, const ImVec2& pos, ImU32 col, ImWchar c) const;
3005 IMGUI_API void RenderText(ImDrawList* draw_list, float size, const ImVec2& pos, ImU32 col, const ImVec4& clip_rect, const char* text_begin, const char* text_end, float wrap_width = 0.0f, bool cpu_fine_clip = false) const;

3017//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
3018// [SECTION] Viewports
3019//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
3020
3021// Flags stored in ImGuiViewport::Flags, giving indications to the platform backends.
3022enum ImGuiViewportFlags_
3023{
3024 ImGuiViewportFlags_None = 0,
3025 ImGuiViewportFlags_IsPlatformWindow = 1 << 0, // Represent a Platform Window
3026 ImGuiViewportFlags_IsPlatformMonitor = 1 << 1, // Represent a Platform Monitor (unused yet)
3027 ImGuiViewportFlags_OwnedByApp = 1 << 2, // Platform Window: is created/managed by the application (rather than a dear imgui backend)
3028 ImGuiViewportFlags_NoDecoration = 1 << 3, // Platform Window: Disable platform decorations: title bar, borders, etc. (generally set all windows, but if ImGuiConfigFlags_ViewportsDecoration is set we only set this on popups/tooltips)
3029 ImGuiViewportFlags_NoTaskBarIcon = 1 << 4, // Platform Window: Disable platform task bar icon (generally set on popups/tooltips, or all windows if ImGuiConfigFlags_ViewportsNoTaskBarIcon is set)
3030 ImGuiViewportFlags_NoFocusOnAppearing = 1 << 5, // Platform Window: Don't take focus when created.
3031 ImGuiViewportFlags_NoFocusOnClick = 1 << 6, // Platform Window: Don't take focus when clicked on.
3032 ImGuiViewportFlags_NoInputs = 1 << 7, // Platform Window: Make mouse pass through so we can drag this window while peaking behind it.
3033 ImGuiViewportFlags_NoRendererClear = 1 << 8, // Platform Window: Renderer doesn't need to clear the framebuffer ahead (because we will fill it entirely).
3034 ImGuiViewportFlags_TopMost = 1 << 9, // Platform Window: Display on top (for tooltips only).
3035 ImGuiViewportFlags_Minimized = 1 << 10, // Platform Window: Window is minimized, can skip render. When minimized we tend to avoid using the viewport pos/size for clipping window or testing if they are contained in the viewport.
3036 ImGuiViewportFlags_NoAutoMerge = 1 << 11, // Platform Window: Avoid merging this window into another host window. This can only be set via ImGuiWindowClass viewport flags override (because we need to now ahead if we are going to create a viewport in the first place!).
3037 ImGuiViewportFlags_CanHostOtherWindows = 1 << 12 // Main viewport: can host multiple imgui windows (secondary viewports are associated to a single window).
3038};
3039
3040// - Currently represents the Platform Window created by the application which is hosting our Dear ImGui windows.
3041// - With multi-viewport enabled, we extend this concept to have multiple active viewports.
3042// - In the future we will extend this concept further to also represent Platform Monitor and support a "no main platform window" operation mode.
3043// - About Main Area vs Work Area:
3044// - Main Area = entire viewport.
3045// - Work Area = entire viewport minus sections used by main menu bars (for platform windows), or by task bar (for platform monitor).
3046// - Windows are generally trying to stay within the Work Area of their host viewport.
3047struct ImGuiViewport
3048{
3049 ImGuiID ID; // Unique identifier for the viewport
3050 ImGuiViewportFlags Flags; // See ImGuiViewportFlags_
3051 ImVec2 Pos; // Main Area: Position of the viewport (Dear ImGui coordinates are the same as OS desktop/native coordinates)
3052 ImVec2 Size; // Main Area: Size of the viewport.
3053 ImVec2 WorkPos; // Work Area: Position of the viewport minus task bars, menus bars, status bars (>= Pos)
3054 ImVec2 WorkSize; // Work Area: Size of the viewport minus task bars, menu bars, status bars (<= Size)
3055 float DpiScale; // 1.0f = 96 DPI = No extra scale.
3056 ImGuiID ParentViewportId; // (Advanced) 0: no parent. Instruct the platform backend to setup a parent/child relationship between platform windows.
3057 ImDrawData* DrawData; // The ImDrawData corresponding to this viewport. Valid after Render() and until the next call to NewFrame().
3058
3059 // Platform/Backend Dependent Data
3060 // Our design separate the Renderer and Platform backends to facilitate combining default backends with each others.
3061 // When our create your own backend for a custom engine, it is possible that both Renderer and Platform will be handled
3062 // by the same system and you may not need to use all the UserData/Handle fields.
3063 // The library never uses those fields, they are merely storage to facilitate backend implementation.
3064 void* RendererUserData; // void* to hold custom data structure for the renderer (e.g. swap chain, framebuffers etc.). generally set by your Renderer_CreateWindow function.
3065 void* PlatformUserData; // void* to hold custom data structure for the OS / platform (e.g. windowing info, render context). generally set by your Platform_CreateWindow function.
3066 void* PlatformHandle; // void* for FindViewportByPlatformHandle(). (e.g. suggested to use natural platform handle such as HWND, GLFWWindow*, SDL_Window*)
3067 void* PlatformHandleRaw; // void* to hold lower-level, platform-native window handle (under Win32 this is expected to be a HWND, unused for other platforms), when using an abstraction layer like GLFW or SDL (where PlatformHandle would be a SDL_Window*)
3068 bool PlatformRequestMove; // Platform window requested move (e.g. window was moved by the OS / host window manager, authoritative position will be OS window position)
3069 bool PlatformRequestResize; // Platform window requested resize (e.g. window was resized by the OS / host window manager, authoritative size will be OS window size)
3070 bool PlatformRequestClose; // Platform window requested closure (e.g. window was moved by the OS / host window manager, e.g. pressing ALT-F4)
3071
3072 ImGuiViewport() { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); }
3073 ~ImGuiViewport() { IM_ASSERT(PlatformUserData == NULL && RendererUserData == NULL); }
3074
3075 // Helpers
3076 ImVec2 GetCenter() const { return ImVec2(Pos.x + Size.x * 0.5f, Pos.y + Size.y * 0.5f); }
3077 ImVec2 GetWorkCenter() const { return ImVec2(WorkPos.x + WorkSize.x * 0.5f, WorkPos.y + WorkSize.y * 0.5f); }
3078};
3079
3080//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
3081// [SECTION] Platform Dependent Interfaces (for e.g. multi-viewport support)
3082//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
3083// [BETA] (Optional) This is completely optional, for advanced users!
3084// If you are new to Dear ImGui and trying to integrate it into your engine, you can probably ignore this for now.
3085//
3086// This feature allows you to seamlessly drag Dear ImGui windows outside of your application viewport.
3087// This is achieved by creating new Platform/OS windows on the fly, and rendering into them.
3088// Dear ImGui manages the viewport structures, and the backend create and maintain one Platform/OS window for each of those viewports.
3089//
3090// See Glossary https://github.com/ocornut/imgui/wiki/Glossary for details about some of the terminology.
3091// See Thread https://github.com/ocornut/imgui/issues/1542 for gifs, news and questions about this evolving feature.
3092//
3093// About the coordinates system:
3094// - When multi-viewports are enabled, all Dear ImGui coordinates become absolute coordinates (same as OS coordinates!)
3095// - So e.g. ImGui::SetNextWindowPos(ImVec2(0,0)) will position a window relative to your primary monitor!
3096// - If you want to position windows relative to your main application viewport, use ImGui::GetMainViewport()->Pos as a base position.
3097//
3098// Steps to use multi-viewports in your application, when using a default backend from the examples/ folder:
3099// - Application: Enable feature with 'io.ConfigFlags |= ImGuiConfigFlags_ViewportsEnable'.
3100// - Backend: The backend initialization will setup all necessary ImGuiPlatformIO's functions and update monitors info every frame.
3101// - Application: In your main loop, call ImGui::UpdatePlatformWindows(), ImGui::RenderPlatformWindowsDefault() after EndFrame() or Render().
3102// - Application: Fix absolute coordinates used in ImGui::SetWindowPos() or ImGui::SetNextWindowPos() calls.
3103//
3104// Steps to use multi-viewports in your application, when using a custom backend:
3105// - Important: THIS IS NOT EASY TO DO and comes with many subtleties not described here!
3106// It's also an experimental feature, so some of the requirements may evolve.
3107// Consider using default backends if you can. Either way, carefully follow and refer to examples/ backends for details.
3108// - Application: Enable feature with 'io.ConfigFlags |= ImGuiConfigFlags_ViewportsEnable'.
3109// - Backend: Hook ImGuiPlatformIO's Platform_* and Renderer_* callbacks (see below).
3110// Set 'io.BackendFlags |= ImGuiBackendFlags_PlatformHasViewports' and 'io.BackendFlags |= ImGuiBackendFlags_PlatformHasViewports'.
3111// Update ImGuiPlatformIO's Monitors list every frame.
3112// Update MousePos every frame, in absolute coordinates.
3113// - Application: In your main loop, call ImGui::UpdatePlatformWindows(), ImGui::RenderPlatformWindowsDefault() after EndFrame() or Render().
3114// You may skip calling RenderPlatformWindowsDefault() if its API is not convenient for your needs. Read comments below.
3115// - Application: Fix absolute coordinates used in ImGui::SetWindowPos() or ImGui::SetNextWindowPos() calls.
3116//
3117// About ImGui::RenderPlatformWindowsDefault():
3118// - This function is a mostly a _helper_ for the common-most cases, and to facilitate using default backends.
3119// - You can check its simple source code to understand what it does.
3120// It basically iterates secondary viewports and call 4 functions that are setup in ImGuiPlatformIO, if available:
3121// Platform_RenderWindow(), Renderer_RenderWindow(), Platform_SwapBuffers(), Renderer_SwapBuffers()
3122// Those functions pointers exists only for the benefit of RenderPlatformWindowsDefault().
3123// - If you have very specific rendering needs (e.g. flipping multiple swap-chain simultaneously, unusual sync/threading issues, etc.),
3124// you may be tempted to ignore RenderPlatformWindowsDefault() and write customized code to perform your renderingg.
3125// You may decide to setup the platform_io's *RenderWindow and *SwapBuffers pointers and call your functions through those pointers,
3126// or you may decide to never setup those pointers and call your code directly. They are a convenience, not an obligatory interface.
3127//-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
3128
3129// (Optional) Access via ImGui::GetPlatformIO()
3130struct ImGuiPlatformIO
3131{
3132 //------------------------------------------------------------------
3133 // Input - Backend interface/functions + Monitor List
3134 //------------------------------------------------------------------
3135
3136 // (Optional) Platform functions (e.g. Win32, GLFW, SDL2)
3137 // For reference, the second column shows which function are generally calling the Platform Functions:
3138 // N = ImGui::NewFrame() ~ beginning of the dear imgui frame: read info from platform/OS windows (latest size/position)
3139 // F = ImGui::Begin(), ImGui::EndFrame() ~ during the dear imgui frame
3140 // U = ImGui::UpdatePlatformWindows() ~ after the dear imgui frame: create and update all platform/OS windows
3141 // R = ImGui::RenderPlatformWindowsDefault() ~ render
3142 // D = ImGui::DestroyPlatformWindows() ~ shutdown
3143 // The general idea is that NewFrame() we will read the current Platform/OS state, and UpdatePlatformWindows() will write to it.
3144 //
3145 // The functions are designed so we can mix and match 2 imgui_impl_xxxx files, one for the Platform (~window/input handling), one for Renderer.
3146 // Custom engine backends will often provide both Platform and Renderer interfaces and so may not need to use all functions.
3147 // Platform functions are typically called before their Renderer counterpart, apart from Destroy which are called the other way.
3148
3149 // Platform function --------------------------------------------------- Called by -----
3150 void (*Platform_CreateWindow)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // . . U . . // Create a new platform window for the given viewport
3151 void (*Platform_DestroyWindow)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // N . U . D //
3152 void (*Platform_ShowWindow)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // . . U . . // Newly created windows are initially hidden so SetWindowPos/Size/Title can be called on them before showing the window
3153 void (*Platform_SetWindowPos)(ImGuiViewport* vp, ImVec2 pos); // . . U . . // Set platform window position (given the upper-left corner of client area)
3154 ImVec2 (*Platform_GetWindowPos)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // N . . . . //
3155 void (*Platform_SetWindowSize)(ImGuiViewport* vp, ImVec2 size); // . . U . . // Set platform window client area size (ignoring OS decorations such as OS title bar etc.)
3156 ImVec2 (*Platform_GetWindowSize)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // N . . . . // Get platform window client area size
3157 void (*Platform_SetWindowFocus)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // N . . . . // Move window to front and set input focus
3158 bool (*Platform_GetWindowFocus)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // . . U . . //
3159 bool (*Platform_GetWindowMinimized)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // N . . . . // Get platform window minimized state. When minimized, we generally won't attempt to get/set size and contents will be culled more easily
3160 void (*Platform_SetWindowTitle)(ImGuiViewport* vp, const char* str); // . . U . . // Set platform window title (given an UTF-8 string)
3161 void (*Platform_SetWindowAlpha)(ImGuiViewport* vp, float alpha); // . . U . . // (Optional) Setup global transparency (not per-pixel transparency)
3162 void (*Platform_UpdateWindow)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // . . U . . // (Optional) Called by UpdatePlatformWindows(). Optional hook to allow the platform backend from doing general book-keeping every frame.
3163 void (*Platform_RenderWindow)(ImGuiViewport* vp, void* render_arg); // . . . R . // (Optional) Main rendering (platform side! This is often unused, or just setting a "current" context for OpenGL bindings). 'render_arg' is the value passed to RenderPlatformWindowsDefault().
3164 void (*Platform_SwapBuffers)(ImGuiViewport* vp, void* render_arg); // . . . R . // (Optional) Call Present/SwapBuffers (platform side! This is often unused!). 'render_arg' is the value passed to RenderPlatformWindowsDefault().
3165 float (*Platform_GetWindowDpiScale)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // N . . . . // (Optional) [BETA] FIXME-DPI: DPI handling: Return DPI scale for this viewport. 1.0f = 96 DPI.
3166 void (*Platform_OnChangedViewport)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // . F . . . // (Optional) [BETA] FIXME-DPI: DPI handling: Called during Begin() every time the viewport we are outputting into changes, so backend has a chance to swap fonts to adjust style.
3167 int (*Platform_CreateVkSurface)(ImGuiViewport* vp, ImU64 vk_inst, const void* vk_allocators, ImU64* out_vk_surface); // (Optional) For a Vulkan Renderer to call into Platform code (since the surface creation needs to tie them both).
3168
3169 // (Optional) Renderer functions (e.g. DirectX, OpenGL, Vulkan)
3170 void (*Renderer_CreateWindow)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // . . U . . // Create swap chain, frame buffers etc. (called after Platform_CreateWindow)
3171 void (*Renderer_DestroyWindow)(ImGuiViewport* vp); // N . U . D // Destroy swap chain, frame buffers etc. (called before Platform_DestroyWindow)
3172 void (*Renderer_SetWindowSize)(ImGuiViewport* vp, ImVec2 size); // . . U . . // Resize swap chain, frame buffers etc. (called after Platform_SetWindowSize)
3173 void (*Renderer_RenderWindow)(ImGuiViewport* vp, void* render_arg); // . . . R . // (Optional) Clear framebuffer, setup render target, then render the viewport->DrawData. 'render_arg' is the value passed to RenderPlatformWindowsDefault().
3174 void (*Renderer_SwapBuffers)(ImGuiViewport* vp, void* render_arg); // . . . R . // (Optional) Call Present/SwapBuffers. 'render_arg' is the value passed to RenderPlatformWindowsDefault().
3175
3176 // (Optional) Monitor list
3177 // - Updated by: app/backend. Update every frame to dynamically support changing monitor or DPI configuration.
3178 // - Used by: dear imgui to query DPI info, clamp popups/tooltips within same monitor and not have them straddle monitors.
3179 ImVector<ImGuiPlatformMonitor> Monitors;
3180
3181 //------------------------------------------------------------------
3182 // Output - List of viewports to render into platform windows
3183 //------------------------------------------------------------------
3184
3185 // Viewports list (the list is updated by calling ImGui::EndFrame or ImGui::Render)
3186 // (in the future we will attempt to organize this feature to remove the need for a "main viewport")
3187 ImVector<ImGuiViewport*> Viewports; // Main viewports, followed by all secondary viewports.
3188 ImGuiPlatformIO() { memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this)); } // Zero clear
3189};
3190
3191// (Optional) This is required when enabling multi-viewport. Represent the bounds of each connected monitor/display and their DPI.
3192// We use this information for multiple DPI support + clamping the position of popups and tooltips so they don't straddle multiple monitors.
3193struct ImGuiPlatformMonitor
3194{
3195 ImVec2 MainPos, MainSize; // Coordinates of the area displayed on this monitor (Min = upper left, Max = bottom right)
3196 ImVec2 WorkPos, WorkSize; // Coordinates without task bars / side bars / menu bars. Used to avoid positioning popups/tooltips inside this region. If you don't have this info, please copy the value for MainPos/MainSize.
3197 float DpiScale; // 1.0f = 96 DPI
3198 ImGuiPlatformMonitor() { MainPos = MainSize = WorkPos = WorkSize = ImVec2(0, 0); DpiScale = 1.0f; }
3199};
